{"title_page": "The Holocaust in Slovakia", "text_new": "{{short description|Systematic dispossession, deportation, and murder of Jews in the Slovak State}}\n{{good article}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n[[File:\"Nebu\u010f slu\u017eobn\u00edkom \u017eida\"\u2014Slovak propaganda poster.jpg|thumb|alt=Man kissing feet of another man with hooked nose, dropping money on his head|A Slovak propaganda poster exhorts readers not to \"be a servant to the Jew\".|upright=1.2]]\n{{The Holocaust sidebar}}\n'''The Holocaust in Slovakia''' was the systematic dispossession, deportation, and murder of Jews in the [[Slovak State]], a [[client state]] of [[Nazi Germany]]. Out of 89,000  [[Slovak Jews|Jews]] in the country in 1940, around 69,000 were murdered during the [[Holocaust]].\n\nIn 1938, Slovakia lost significant territory to Hungary according to the [[First Vienna Award]]; the following year, the ruling [[ethnonationalist]] [[Slovak People's Party]] declared independence from [[Second Czechoslovak Republic|Czechoslovakia]] with German protection. Slovak propaganda blamed the Jews for the territorial losses. Jews were targeted for discrimination and harassment, including the [[Aryanization in Slovakia|confiscation of property and businesses]]. The exclusion of Jews from the economy impoverished the community, which encouraged the government to conscript them for forced labor. \n\nIn 1941, the Slovak government negotiated with Nazi Germany for the mass deportation of Jews to [[German-occupied Poland]]. Between March and October 1942, [[List of Holocaust transports from Slovakia|58,000 Jews were deported]] to [[Auschwitz concentration camp]] and the [[Lublin District]] of the [[General Governorate]] in German-occupied Poland; only a few hundred survived. The Slovak government organized the transports and paid 500 [[Reichsmarks]] per Jew for the supposed cost of resettlement. The persecution of Jews resumed in August 1944, when [[German occupation of Slovakia|Germany invaded Slovakia]] and triggered the [[Slovak National Uprising]]. Another 13,500 Jews were deported and hundreds to thousands were murdered in Slovakia by [[Einsatzgruppe H]] and the [[Hlinka Guard Emergency Divisions]].\n\nSurvivors faced [[secondary antisemitism|renewed antisemitism]] and difficulty regaining stolen property; most emigrated. The [[Communist Party of Czechoslovakia|postwar Communist regime]] banned discussion of the Holocaust, the ban was only removed after the [[Velvet Revolution|fall of the Communist regime]] in 1989. The Slovak government's complicity in the Holocaust remains a contentious issue in the country.\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Background ==\n{{further|History of the Jews in Slovakia}}\n\n[[File:Synagogue Zilina 1931.jpg|thumb|left|The [[New Synagogue (\u017dilina)|New Synagogue]] in [[\u017dilina]] shortly after completion, {{circa|1931}}]]\nBefore 1939, Slovakia had never been an independent country. It had been part of the [[Kingdom of Hungary]] for a thousand years; after World War I, it became part of [[First Czechoslovak Republic|Czechoslovakia]].{{sfn|De\u00e1k|2015|p=31}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=18}} Following [[Jewish emancipation]] in 1896, many Jews had adopted Hungarian language and customs in order to advance in society. Many Jews moved to cities and joined the professions; others remained in the countryside, mostly working as artisans, merchants, and shopkeepers.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=18}}{{sfn|Lorman|2019|pp=47\u201348}} Their multilingualism helped them advance in business, but put them in conflict with [[Slovak nationalism]].{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=18}}{{sfn|Lorman|2019|p=48}}{{sfn|L\u00f4n\u010d\u00edkov\u00e1|2017|p=85}} Traditional [[religious antisemitism]] was joined by the stereotypical view of Jews as exploiters of poor Slovaks ([[economic antisemitism]]), and a form of \"national anti-Semitism\" that accused Jews of sympathizing with [[Hungarian irredentism|Hungarian]] and later [[Czechoslovakism|Czechoslovak national aims]].{{sfn|L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek|2013|p=35}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|pp=18\u201319}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|pp=49\u201350}}\n\nIn the 1930s, economic underdevelopment and perceptions of discrimination in Czechoslovakia{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=842}} led a plurality (about one-third) of Slovaks{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=79}} to support the conservative, [[ethnonationalist]] [[Slovak People's Party]] ({{lang-sk|Hlinkova slovensk\u00e1 \u013eudov\u00e1 strana}}: HS\u013dS).{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=842}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2018|p=5}} HS\u013dS viewed minority groups such as Czechs, Hungarians, Jews, and [[Romani people]] as a destructive influence on the Slovak nation,{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2018|p=5}} and presented [[autonomous region|Slovak autonomy]] as the solution to Slovakia's problems.{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=79}} The party began to emphasize antisemitism during the late 1930s following a wave of Jewish refugees from Austria after its [[Anschluss|1938 annexation]] by [[Nazi Germany]] and anti-Jewish laws passed by the neighboring states of Hungary, [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]], and [[Kingdom of Romania|Romania]].{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=87}}\n\n==Slovak independence==\n[[File:Slovakia borderHungary.png|thumb|upright=1.6|alt=Map of Slovakia reflecting southern losses to Hungary|Slovak territorial losses to Hungary in 1938 and 1939]]\n[[File:Slovak Republic 1939 45 Administrative Map.png|thumb|upright=1.6|alt=Color-coded map of the Slovak Republic|Administrative regions of the Slovak State (1939\u20131945)]]\nThe September 1938 [[Munich Agreement]] ceded the [[Sudetenland]], the German-speaking region of the [[Czech lands]], to Germany. HS\u013dS took advantage of the ensuing political chaos to declare Slovakia's autonomy on 6 October 1938. [[Jozef Tiso]], a Catholic priest and HS\u013dS leader, became prime minister of the Slovak autonomous region.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=842}}{{sfn|L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek|2013|pp=16\u201317}} Catholicism, the religion of 80% of the country's inhabitants, was key to the regime with many of its leaders being bishops, priests, or laymen.{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|pp=179\u2013180}}{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|pp=81\u201382}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=23}} Under Tiso's leadership, the Slovak government opened [[First Vienna Award#Negotiations in Kom\u00e1rno|negotiations in Kom\u00e1rno]] with Hungary regarding their border. The dispute was submitted to [[First Vienna Award|arbitration in Vienna]] by Nazi Germany and [[Kingdom of Italy under Fascism (1922\u20131943)|Fascist Italy]]. Hungary was awarded much of southern Slovakia on 2 November 1938, including 40 percent of Slovakia's arable land and 270,000 people who had declared Czechoslovak ethnicity.{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=161, 163, 166}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|pp=842\u2013843}} HS\u013dS consolidated its power by passing an  [[enabling act]], banning opposing political parties, shutting down independent newspapers, distributing antisemitic and anti-Czech propaganda, and founding the paramilitary [[Hlinka Guard]].{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=842}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=20}} Parties for the German and Hungarian minorities were allowed under HS\u013dS hegemony, and the [[German Party (Slovakia)|German Party]] formed the {{lang|de|[[Freiwillige Schutzstaffel]]}} militia.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=842}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|pp=20\u201321}} HS\u013dS imprisoned thousands of its political opponents,{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=22}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|p=91}} but never carried out an execution.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=9}} [[1938 Slovak parliamentary election|Un-free elections in December 1938]] resulted in a 95-percent vote for HS\u013dS.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=843}}{{sfn|Lorman|2019|p=216}}\n\nOn 14 March 1939, the [[Slovak State]] proclaimed its independence under German protection.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=843}} Germany annexed and invaded the Czech [[rump state]] the following day, and Hungary seized [[Carpathian Ruthenia]] with German acquiescence.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=843}}{{sfn|L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek|2013|pp=16\u201317}} In a [[German-Slovak treaty of 23 March 1939|treaty signed on 23 March]], Slovakia renounced much of its foreign-policy and military autonomy to Germany in exchange for border guarantees and economic assistance.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=843}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=184}} It was neither fully independent nor a German puppet state, but occupied an intermediate status.{{efn|Views differ on this point. [[Istv\u00e1n De\u00e1k]] writes, \"Despite the claims of some historians, [Slovakia] functioned not as a puppet state but as Nazi Germany\u2019s first but not last Slavic-speaking military ally\".{{sfn|De\u00e1k|2015|pp=35\u201336}} [[Tatjana T\u00f6nsmeyer]], who maintains that the puppet-state narrative overstates German influence and understates Slovakia's autonomy, notes that Slovak authorities frequently avoided implementing measures pushed by the Germans when such measures did not suit Slovak priorities. According to German historian Barbara Hutzelmann, \"Although the country was not independent, in the full sense of the word, it would be too simplistic to see this German-protected state ({{lang|de|Schutzstaat}}) simply as a 'puppet regime'.\"{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=168}} [[Ivan Kamenec]], however, emphasizes German influence on Slovak internal and external politics and describes it as a \"German satellite\".{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|pp=180\u2013182}}}}  In October 1939, Tiso (leader of the conservative/[[clericalism|clerical]] branch of HS\u013dS) became president; [[Vojtech Tuka]], leader of the party's radical/fascist wing, was appointed prime minister. Both wings of the party struggled for Germany's favor.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=843}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=184}} The radical wing of the party was fascist and pro-German, while the conservatives favored autonomy from Germany;{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=203}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=184}}  the radicals relied on the Hlinka Guard and German support,{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=184}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=216}} while Tiso was popular among the clergy and the population.{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|pp=184\u2013185}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=172, 216}} A 1940 census found that 89,000 Jews lived in the Slovak State, 3.4 percent of the population.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}} The largest number of Jews lived in the eastern [[\u0160ari\u0161]]-[[Zempl\u00edn (region)|Zempl\u00edn]] region,{{sfn|Ward|2002|p=584}} and 15,000 lived in [[Bratislava]].{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=65}}{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=17}} Around 5,000 and 6,000 Jews emigrated between 1938 and 1940, and 45,000 lived in the areas ceded to Hungary.{{sfn|Ward|2015|pp=94, 96}}{{sfn|Legge|2018|p=227}}\n\n== Anti-Jewish measures (1938\u20131941) ==\n===Overview===\nImmediately after it came to power in 1938, the autonomous government began firing Jewish government employees.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=165}} The [[Committee for the Solution of the Jewish Question]] <!-- Komisiu pre rie\u0161enie \u017eidovskej ot\u00e1zky --> was founded on 23 January 1939 to discuss anti-Jewish legislation.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=844}}{{sfn|Hallon|2007|p=149}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=22}}  The state-sponsored media demonized Jews as \"[[enemies of the state]]\" and [[enemy of the people|of the Slovak nation]].{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=844}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=188}}   Jewish businesses were robbed,{{sfn|Legge|2018|p=226}} and physical attacks on Jews occurred both spontaneously and at the instigation of the Hlinka Guard and Freiwillige Schutzstaffel.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2013|pp=551\u2013552}} On his first radio address following the establishment of the Slovak State in 1939, Tiso emphasized his desire to \"solve the Jewish Question\";{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2018|p=11}} anti-Jewish legislation was the only concrete measure that he promised.{{sfn|Lorman|2019|p=226}}  The persecution of Jews was a key element of the state's domestic policy.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=844}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2018|p=8}} Discriminatory measures affected all aspects of life, to isolate and dispossess Jews before deporting them.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=844}}\n\n=== 1938 deportation and emigration===\n{{main|1938 deportation of Jews from Slovakia}}\nIn the days after the announcement of the [[First Vienna Award]], antisemitic rioting broke out in Bratislava; newspapers justified the riots because of Jews' alleged support for Hungary during the partition negotiations. [[Adolf Eichmann]], who had been sent to Bratislava, coauthored a plan with Tiso and other HS\u013dS politicians to deport impoverished and foreign Jews to the ceded territory.{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=92}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=21}} Meanwhile, Jews with a net worth of over 500,000 [[Czechoslovak koruna]] (K\u010ds) were arrested in an unsuccessful attempt to prevent [[capital flight]].{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=92}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=844}}  Between 4 and 7 November,{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=844}}  4,000{{sfn|Frankl|2019|p=97}} or 7,600 Jews were deported, in a chaotic, [[pogrom]]-like operation in which Hlinka Guard, {{lang|de|Freiwillige Schutzstaffel}}, and the German Party participated.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=21}} The deportees included young children, the elderly, and pregnant women.{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|2014|p=506}} A few days later, Tiso canceled the operation; most of the Jews were allowed to return home in December.{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=93}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=22}} More than 800 were confined to makeshift tent camps at [[Ve\u013ek\u00fd K\u00fdr]], [[Miloslavov]], and [[\u0160amor\u00edn]] on the new Slovak\u2013Hungarian border during the winter.{{sfn|Frankl|2019|p=103, 112}} The deportations occurred just after Germany's {{lang|de|[[Polenaktion]]}}, a similar event;{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=21}}{{sfn|Frankl|2019|p=95}} attracted international criticism,{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=844}} reduced British investment, increasing dependence on German capital;{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=96}} and were a rehearsal for the 1942 deportations.{{sfn|Johnson|2005|p=316}} \n\n[[File:Temporary Slovak passport issued in 1940 to a Jewish refugee family.jpg|thumb|left|alt=See caption|Temporary passport issued in 1940 to a Jew who fled to Italy]]\n\nInitially, many Jews believed that the measures taken against them would be temporary.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=26}} Nevertheless, some attempted to emigrate and take their property with them. Between December 1938 and February 1939, more than 2.25 million K\u010ds were transferred illegally to the Czech lands, the Netherlands, and the United Kingdom; additional amounts were transferred legally. Slovak government officials took advantage of the circumstances to purchase the property of wealthy Jewish emigrants at a significant discount, a precursor to the state-sponsored transfer of Jewish property ([[Aryanization]]).{{sfn|Hallon|2007|pp=149\u2013150}} Interest in emigration among  Jews surged after the [[invasion of Poland]], as Jewish refugees from Poland told of atrocities there. Although  the Slovak government  encouraged Jews to emigrate, it refused to allow the export of foreign currency, ensuring that  most attempts remained unsuccessful. No country was eager to accept Jewish refugees, and the [[White Paper of 1939|tight limits]] on legal emigration to [[Mandatory Palestine]] prevented Jews from seeking refuge there. In 1940, Bratislava became a hub for {{lang|he|[[Aliyah Bet]]}} operatives organizing illegal immigration to Palestine, one of whom, [[Aron Gr\u00fcnhut]], helped 1,365 Slovak, Czech, Hungarian, and Austrian Jews emigrate. By early 1941, further emigration was impossible; even Jews who received valid United States visas were not allowed transit visas through Nazi Germany.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=26}} The total number of Slovak Jewish emigrants has been estimated at 5,000 to 6,000.{{sfn|Ward|2015|pp=94, 96}}{{sfn|Legge|2018|p=227}} \n{{clear}}\n\n=== Aryanization ===\n[[File:Antisemitick\u00e1 Propaganda na Slovensku.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|alt=Non-Jewish man kicks a stereotypically dressed Orthodox Jew|Antisemitic government propaganda]]\nAryanization in Slovakia, the seizure of Jewish-owned property and exclusion of Jews from the economy,{{sfn|Hallon|2007|p=148}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=25}} was justified by the stereotype (reinforced by HS\u013dS propaganda) of Jews obtaining their wealth by oppressing Slovaks.{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek|2018|p=43}}{{sfn|T\u00f6nsmeyer|2007|p=90}}{{sfn|L\u00f4n\u010d\u00edkov\u00e1|2017|p=85}} Between 1939 and 1942, the HS\u013dS regime received widespread popular support by promising Slovak citizens that they would be enriched by property confiscated from Jews and other minorities.{{sfn|L\u00f4n\u010d\u00edkov\u00e1|2017|p=85}}{{sfn|Cichopek-Gajraj|2018|p=254}}  This was a significant amount of money; in 1940, Jews registered more than 4.322 billion [[Slovak koruna]] (Ks) in property (38 percent of the national wealth).{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=24}}{{efn|Equivalent to [[United States dollar|USD$]]108 million at the time,{{sfn|Foreign Claims Settlement Commission|1968|p=655}} or ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|108,000,000|1942|r=0}}}} today.{{sfn| Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis|2019}} All currency conversions are made from the [[Foreign Claims Settlement Commission]]'s determination of wartime exchange rate.{{sfn|Foreign Claims Settlement Commission|1968|p=655}}}} The process might more aptly be described as \"Slovakization\",{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=28}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=174}}{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|2014|p=510}}  as the Slovak government took steps to ensure that ethnic Slovaks, rather than Germans or other minorities, received the stolen Jewish property. Due to the intervention of the German Party and Nazi Germany, ethnic Germans received 8.3 percent of the stolen property,{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=174}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=28}} but most German applicants were refused, underscoring the freedom of action of the Slovak government.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=28}}\n\nThe first anti-Jewish law, passed on 18 April 1939 and not systematically enforced, was a {{lang|la|[[numerus clausus]]}} four-percent quota of the numbers of Jews allowed to practice law; Jews were also forbidden to write for Christian publications.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}}{{sfn|Rothkirchen|2001|pp=596\u2013597}}{{sfn|Ward|2015|p=97}} The Land Reform Act of February 1940 turned {{convert|101423|ha}} of land owned by 4,943 Jews, about 40 percent of it arable, over to the State Land Office; the land officially passed to the state in May 1942.{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=24}}{{efn|The Land Reform Act did not explicitly target Jews, but it was rarely enforced against non-Jewish landowners.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=25}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=221}}}} The First Aryanization Law was passed in April 1940. {{anchor|Voluntary Aryanization}}Through a process known as \"voluntary Aryanization\", Jewish business owners could suggest a \"qualified Christian candidate\" who would assume at least a 51-percent stake in the company.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}} Under the law, 50 businesses out of more than 12,000 were Aryanized and 179 were liquidated.{{sfn|Hallon|2007|p=151}} HS\u013dS radicals{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}} and the Slovak State's German backers believed that voluntary Aryanization was too soft on the Jews.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=169}}\n\n[[File:Salzburg Conference montage (Tiso and Hitler facing camera).jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|left|[[Jozef Tiso]] and [[Adolf Hitler]] at the [[Salzburg Conference]], 1940]]\nAt the July 1940 [[Salzburg Conference]], German negotiators convinced the Slovaks to replace several members of the cabinet  with  reliably pro-German radicals.{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=177}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|pp=843\u2013844}} [[Ferdinand \u010eur\u010dansk\u00fd]] was replaced as interior minister by Alexander Mach, who aligned the anti-Jewish policy of the Slovak State with that in Germany.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=27}}{{sfn|Legge|2018|p=228}} Another result of the Salzburg talks was the appointment of SS officer [[Dieter Wisliceny]] as a \"[[Judenberater|Jewish adviser]]\" for Slovakia; he arrived in Slovakia in August.{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=65}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=27}} He aimed to impoverish the Jewish community so it became a burden on non-Jewish Slovaks, who would then agree to deport them.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=215}} At Wisliceny's instigation, the Slovak government created the [[Central Economic Office]] (\u00daH\u00da), led by Slovak official {{ill|August\u00edn Mor\u00e1vek|cs||de||sk}} and under Tuka's control, in September 1940.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|pp=169\u2013170}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=27}} The \u00daH\u00da was tasked with assuming ownership of Jewish-owned property.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}} Jews were required to register their property; their bank accounts (valued at 245 million Ks in August 1941){{efn|Equivalent to USD$6.125 million at the time,{{sfn|Foreign Claims Settlement Commission|1968|p=655}} or ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|6,125,000|1942|r=0}}}} today.{{sfn| Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis|2019}}}} were frozen, and Jews were allowed to withdraw only 1,000 Ks (later 150 Ks) per week.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}}{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=24}} The 22,000 Jews who worked in salaried employment were targeted:{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=769}} non-Jews had to obtain \u00daH\u00da permission to employ Jews and pay a fee.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}} By mid-1940, the position of Jews in the Slovak economy had been largely wiped out.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=25}} \n\nA second Aryanization law was passed in November, mandating the expropriation of Jewish property and the Aryanization or liquidation of Jewish businesses.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=170}} In a corrupt process overseen by Mor\u00e1vek's office, 10,000 Jewish businesses (mostly shops) were liquidated and the remainder \u2013 about 2,300 \u2013 were Aryanized.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}}{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=24}}{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|pp=769\u2013770}} Liquidation benefited small Slovak businesses competing with Jewish enterprises, and Aryanization was applied to larger Jewish-owned companies which were acquired by competitors. In many cases, Aryanizers inexpert in business struck deals with former Jewish owners and employees so the Jews would keep working for the company.{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|pp=770\u2013771}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=70}}  The Aryanization of businesses did not bring the anticipated revenue into the Slovak treasury, and only 288 of the liquidated businesses produced income for the state by July 1942.{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|pp=24\u201325}}  The Aryanization and liquidation of businesses was nearly complete by January 1942,{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|pp=770\u2013771}} resulting in 64,000 of 89,000 Jews losing their means of support.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}}{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=26}}  Manufactured Jewish impoverishment was a pressing social problem for the Slovak government, which it \"solved\" in 1942 by deporting the unemployed Jews.{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=25}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=50}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=38}}\n\nAryanization resulted in immense financial loss to Slovakia and great destruction of wealth. The state failed to raise substantial funds from the sale of Jewish property and businesses, and most of its gains came from the confiscation of Jewish-owned bank accounts and financial securities. The main beneficiaries of Aryanization were members of Slovak fascist political parties and paramilitary groups, who were eager to acquire Jewish property but had little  expertise in running Jewish businesses.{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|pp=24\u201325}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|pp=173\u2013174}} During the republic's existence, the government gained 1,100 million Ks from Aryanization and spent 900\u2013950 million Ks on enforcing anti-Jewish measures.{{efn|Gain equivalent to USD$27.5 million at the time,{{sfn|Foreign Claims Settlement Commission|1968|p=655}} or ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|27,500,000|1942|r=0}}}} today.{{sfn| Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis|2019}} Loss equivalent to $22.5 million{{sfn|Foreign Claims Settlement Commission|1968|p=655}} or ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|22,500,000|1942|r=0}}}} today.{{sfn| Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis|2019}}}} In 1942, it paid the German government an additional 300 million Ks for the deportation of 58,000 Jews.{{sfn|Dreyfus|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=25}}\n\n=== Jewish Center ===\n{{Main|\u00dastred\u0148a \u017didov}}\nWhen Wisliceny arrived, all Jewish community organizations were dissolved and the Jews were forced to form the \u00dastred\u0148a \u017didov (Jewish Center, \u00da\u017d, subordinate to the \u00daH\u00da) in September 1940.{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p=165}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=27}} The first {{lang|de|[[Judenrat]]}} outside the Reich and German-occupied Poland, the \u00da\u017d was the only secular Jewish organization allowed to exist in Slovakia; membership was required of all Jews.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}}{{sfn|Bauer|2002|p=176}} Leaders of the Jewish community were divided about how to respond to this development. Although some argued that the \u00da\u017d would be used to implement anti-Jewish measures, more saw participation in the \u00da\u017d as a way to help their fellow Jews by delaying the implementation of such measures and alleviating poverty.{{sfn|Fatran|2002|p=143}}{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p=165}} The first leader of the \u00da\u017d was [[Heinrich Schwartz]], who thwarted anti-Jewish orders to the best of his ability: he sabotaged a census of Jews in eastern Slovakia which was intended to justify their removal to the west of the country; Wisliceny had him arrested in April 1941.{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p=166}}{{sfn|Fatran|2002|pp=144\u2013145}}{{sfn|Rothkirchen|2001|p=597}} The Central Economic Office appointed the more cooperative Arpad Sebestyen as Schwartz' replacement.{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=70}} Wisliceny set up a [[\u00dastred\u0148a \u017didov#Special Affairs|Department for Special Affairs]] in the \u00da\u017d to ensure the prompt implementation of Nazi decrees, appointing the collaborationist [[Karol Hochberg]] (a Viennese Jew) as its director.{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p=166}}{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=70}}\n\n=== Forced labor ===\n{{further|\u00dastred\u0148a \u017didov#Retraining camps}}\n[[File:Sere\u010f m\u00fazeum holokaustu 04.jpg|thumb|alt=Long, low building with a pitched roof|Restored barracks at [[Sere\u010f concentration camp]]]]\nJews serving in the army were segregated in a labor unit in April 1939, and were stripped of their rank at the end of the year. From 1940, male Jews and Romani people were obliged to work for the national defense (generally manual labor on construction projects) for two months every year. All recruits considered Jewish or Romani were allocated to the [[Sixth Labor Battalion]], which worked at military construction sites at [[Sabinov]], [[Liptovsk\u00fd Sv\u00e4t\u00fd Peter]], [[L\u00e1b]], [[Sv\u00e4t\u00fd Jur]], and [[Zohor]] the following year.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}} Although the Ministry of Defense was pressured by the Ministry of the Interior to release the Jews for deportation in 1942, it refused.{{sfn|Bachn\u00e1r|2011}} The battalion was disbanded in 1943, and the Jewish laborers were sent to a number of work camps.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=38}} \n\nThe first labor centers were established in early 1941 by the \u00da\u017d as retraining courses for Jews forced into unemployment; 13,612 Jews had applied for the courses by February, far exceeding the programs' capacity.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007| p= 177}} On 4 July, the Slovak government issued a decree conscripting all Jewish men aged 18 to 60 for labor.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=30}} Although the \u00da\u017d had to supplement the workers' pay to meet the legal minimum, the labor camps greatly increased the living standard of Jews impoverished by Aryanization.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=180}} By September, 5,500 Jews were performing manual labor for private companies at about 80 small labor centers,{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}} most of which were dissolved in the final months of 1941 as part of the preparation for deportation. Construction began on three larger camps \u2013 [[Sere\u010f concentration camp|Sere\u010f]], [[Nov\u00e1ky labor camp|Nov\u00e1ky]], and [[Vyhne labor camp|Vyhne]] \u2013 in September of that year.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=180}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|pp=846\u2013847}}\n\n=== Jewish Code ===\n[[File:\u013dudov\u00e9 noviny 1941.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|left|alt=See caption|Headline of 21 September 1941 propaganda-ministry publication: \"We've dealt with the Jews! The strictest laws against Jews are Slovakia's.\"<!-- translation by User:Buidhe -->]]\nIn accordance with [[Catholic Church and race|Catholic teaching on race]], antisemitic laws initially defined Jews by religion rather than ancestry; Jews who were baptized before 1918 were considered Christian.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=169}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|pp=24, 29}} By September 1940, Jews were banned from secondary and higher education and from all non-Jewish schools, and forbidden from owning motor vehicles, sports equipment, or radios.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=215}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=28}} Local authorities had imposed anti-Jewish measures on their own; the head of the \u0160ari\u0161-Zempl\u00edn region ordered local Jews to wear a yellow band around their left arm from 5 April 1941, leading to attacks.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=845}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=29}} As the focus shifted to restricting Jews' civil rights rather than depriving them of their property, [[Department 14]] of the Ministry of the Interior was formed to enforce anti-Jewish measures.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=181}} \n\nThe Slovak parliament passed the Jewish Code on 9 September 1941, which contained 270 anti-Jewish articles.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}} Based on the [[Nuremberg Laws]], the code defined Jews in terms of ancestry, banned intermarriage, and required that all Jews over six years old wear a [[Yellow badge|yellow star]]. The Jewish Code excluded Jews from public life, restricting the hours that they were allowed to travel and shop, and barring them from clubs, organizations, and public events.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|pp=188\u2013189}} In addition, Jews had to pay a 20 percent tax on all property.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=29}} Slovak propaganda boasted that the Jewish Code was the strictest set of anti-Jewish laws in Europe. The president could issue [[presidential exemption (Slovak State)|exemption]]s protecting individual Jews from the law.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}}  Employed Jews were initially exempt from some of the code's requirements, such as wearing the star.{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=774}} \n\nThe racial definition of Jews was criticized by the Catholic Church, and converts were eventually exempted from some of the requirements.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|pp=260\u2013262}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=226}} The Hlinka Guard and {{lang|de|Freiwillige Schutzstaffel}} increased assaults on Jews, engaged in antisemitic demonstrations on a daily basis, and harassed non-Jews judged insufficiently antisemitic.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|pp=186\u2013187}} The law enabled the Central Economic Office to force Jews to change their residence.{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=775}} This provision was put into effect on 4 October 1941, when 10,000 of 15,000 Jews in Bratislava (who were not employed or intermarried) were ordered to move to fourteen towns.{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=775}}{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|2016|pp=315, 321}} The relocation was paid for and carried out by the \u00da\u017d's Department of Special Tasks.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|pp=191\u2013192}} Although the Jews were ordered to leave by 31 December 1941, fewer than 7,000 people had moved by March 1942.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=192}}{{sfn|Hradsk\u00e1|2016|p=321}}\n\n== {{anchor|Deportations}}Deportations (1942) ==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-A0706-0018-029, Sowjetunion, Storow, Juden vor Exekution.jpg|alt=crowd of people with some digging|thumb|Jews forced to dig their own graves in [[Zboriv]], Ukraine, 4 July 1941]]\nThe highest levels of the Slovak government were aware by late 1941 of mass murders of Jews in German-occupied territories.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=31}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=175}} In July 1941, Wisliceny organized a visit by Slovak government officials to several forced-labor camps run by [[Organization Schmelt]] for the [[Reichsautobahn]] that imprisoned Jews in [[East Upper Silesia]]. The visitors understood that Jews in the camps lived under conditions which would eventually cause their deaths.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|pp=30\u201331}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=170}} Slovak soldiers [[Slovak Expeditionary Army Group|participated]] in the German invasions of Poland and the Soviet Union;{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=23}} they brought word of the mass shootings of Jews, and participated in at least one of the massacres.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=176}} Some Slovaks were aware of the 1941 [[Kamianets-Podilskyi massacre]], in which 23,600 Jews, many of them deported from Hungary, were shot in western Ukraine.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=39}}{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=224}} Defense minister [[Ferdinand \u010catlo\u0161]] and general [[Jozef Turanec]] reported massacres in [[Zhytomyr]] to Tiso by February 1942.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=31}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}} Both bishop [[Karol Kme\u0165ko]] and papal {{lang|fr|[[charg\u00e9 d'affaires]]}} [[Giuseppe Burzio]] confronted the president with reliable reports of the mass murder of Jewish civilians in the Ukraine.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=232}} However, the Slovak government was not aware of the [[Final Solution|Nazi plan to murder all Jews]].{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=71}}\n\nIn mid-1941, the Germans demanded (per previous agreements) another 20,000 Slovak laborers to work in Germany. Slovakia refused to send gentile Slovaks and instead offered an equal number of Jewish workers, although it did not want to be burdened with their families.{{sfn|Bauer|2002|pp=176\u2013177}}{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=65}} A letter sent 15 October 1941 indicates that plans were being made for the mass murder of Jews in the [[Lublin Reservation]] of the [[General Government]] to make room for deported Jews from Slovakia and Germany.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=295, 428}}  In late October, Tiso, Tuka, Mach, and \u010catlo\u0161 visited the [[Wolf's Lair]] (near [[Rastenburg]], [[East Prussia]]) and met with [[Adolf Hitler]]. No record survives of this meeting, at which the deportation of Jews from Slovakia was probably first discussed, leading to historiographical debate over who proposed the idea.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2013|pp=570, 572}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}} Even if the Germans made the offer, the Slovak decision was not motivated by German pressure.{{sfn|L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek|2013|p=110}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2018|p=10}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}} In November 1941, the Slovak government permitted the German government to deport the 659 Slovak Jews living in the Reich and the [[Protectorate of Bohemia and Moravia]],{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}}{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=463}} with the proviso that their confiscated property be passed to Slovakia.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=285}} This was the first step towards deporting Jews from Slovakia,{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=114}} which Tuka discussed with Wisliceny in early 1942.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=229}} As indicated by a cable from the German ambassador to Slovakia, [[Hanns Ludin]], the Slovaks responded \"with enthusiasm\" to the idea.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=116}}\n\nTuka presented the deportation proposals to the government on 3 March, and they were debated in parliament three days later.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=846}} On 15 May, parliament approved [[Decree 68/1942]], which retroactively legalized the deportation of Jews, authorized the removal of their citizenship, and regulated exemptions.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=233}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=34}} Opposition centered on economic, moral, and legal obstacles, but, as Mach later stated, \"every [legislator] who has spoken on this issue has said that we should get rid of Jews\".{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=230}} The official Catholic representative, Bishop of [[Spi\u0161]] [[J\u00e1n Vojta\u0161\u0161\u00e1k]], only requested separate settlements in Poland for Jews who had converted to Christianity.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=32}} The Slovaks agreed to pay 500 [[Reichsmark]]s per Jew deported (ostensibly to cover shelter, food, retraining and housing){{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=32}}{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|pp=776\u2013777}} and an additional fee to the {{lang|de|[[Deutsche Reichsbahn]]}} for transport.{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=778}} (The 500 Reichsmark fee was equivalent to about [[United States dollar|USD$]]125 at the time,{{sfn|Foreign Claims Settlement Commission|1968|p=655}} or  ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|125|1942|r=0}}}} today).{{sfn| Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis|2019}} The Germans promised in exchange that the Jews would never return, and Slovakia could keep all confiscated property.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=34}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=176}}  Except for Croatia (which paid 30 Reichsmarks per person), Slovakia was the only country which paid to deport its Jewish population.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2011|p=121}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2013|p=555}}\n\n==={{anchor|Enaction|First phase|Implementation}}First phase===\n{{further |List of Holocaust transports from Slovakia#Initial phase}}\n[[File:Sere\u010f m\u00fazeum holokaustu 08.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.1 |alt=Photograph of a restored train car, with its sliding door open, used to transport Slovak Jews | Restored train car used to transport Slovak Jews. S\u017d stands for [[Slovensk\u00e9 \u017deleznice]] (Slovak Railways).]]\nThe original deportation plan, approved in February 1942, entailed the deportation of 7,000 women to [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz]] and 13,000 men to [[Majdanek concentration camp|Majdanek]] as forced laborers.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=324\u2013325}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=301}} Department 14 organized the deportations,{{sfn|Ward|2002|p=576}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}  while the Slovak Transport Ministry provided the [[Holocaust trains|cattle cars]].{{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=777}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=216, 230}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=34}}  Lists of those to be deported were drawn up by Department 14 based on statistical data provided by the Jewish Center's Department for Special Tasks.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=301}} At the border station in [[Zwardon]], the Hlinka Guard handed the transports off to the German {{lang|de|[[Schutzpolizei (Nazi Germany)|Schutzpolizei]]}}.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=32}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=153}} Slovak officials promised that deportees would be allowed to return home after a fixed period,{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=302}} and many Jews initially believed that it was better to report for deportation rather than risk reprisals against their families.{{sfn|Bauer|2002|pp=177\u2013178}} On 25 March 1942, the [[First mass transport of Jews to Auschwitz concentration camp|first transport]] departed from [[Poprad transit camp]] for Auschwitz with 1,000 unmarried Jewish women between the ages of 16 and 45.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}  During the first wave of deportations (which ended on 2 April), 6,000 young, single Jews were deported to Auschwitz and Majdanek.{{sfn|Ward|2002|p=579}}\n\nMembers of the Hlinka Guard, the {{lang|de|Freiwillige Schutzstaffel}}, and the [[gendarmerie]] were in charge of rounding up the Jews, guarding the transit centers, and eventually forcing them into train cars for deportation.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}{{sfn|Cichopek|2014|pp=15\u201316}} However, there was a German captain stationed at each of the concentration centers.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=66}} Official exemptions were supposed to keep Jews from being deported, but local authorities sometimes deported exemption-holders.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|p=264}} The victims were given only four hours' warning, to prevent them from escaping. Beatings and forcible shaving were commonplace, as was subjecting Jews to invasive searches to uncover hidden valuables.{{sfn|Sokolovi\u010d|2013|pp=346\u2013347}} Although some guards and local officials accepted bribes to keep Jews off the transports, the victim would typically be deported on the next train.{{sfn|Kamenec|2011b|p=107}} Others took advantage of their power to rape Jewish women.{{sfn|Sokolovi\u010d|2013|p=347}} Jews were only allowed to bring {{convert|50|kg}} of personal items with them, but even this was frequently stolen.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=66}}\n\n===Family transports===\n{{further |List of Holocaust transports from Slovakia#Transports to Lublin|List of Holocaust transports from Slovakia#Transports to Auschwitz}}\nSS leader [[Reinhard Heydrich]] visited Bratislava on 10 April, and he and Tuka agreed that further deportations would target whole families and eventually remove all Jews from Slovakia.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=325}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|pp=222\u2013223}} The family transports began on 11 April, and took their victims to the Lublin district.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=325\u2013326}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|pp=313, 320}}  During the first half of June 1942 ten transports stopped briefly at Majdanek, where able-bodied men were [[selection (Holocaust)|selected]] for labor; the trains continued to Sobib\u00f3r, where the remaining victims were murdered.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=325\u2013326}} Most of the trains brought their victims (30,000 in total){{sfn|Hilberg|2003|p=785}} to ghettos whose inhabitants had been recently deported to the [[Be\u0142\u017cec extermination camp|Be\u0142\u017cec]] or Sobib\u00f3r [[death camps]]. Some groups stayed only briefly before they were deported again to the death camps, while other groups remained in the ghettos for months or years.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=325\u2013326}}  Some of the deportees ended up in the forced-labor camps in the Lublin area (such as [[Poniatowa concentration camp|Poniatowa]], [[D\u0119blin\u2013Irena Ghetto#Luftwaffe camp|D\u0119blin\u2013Irena]], and [[Krych\u00f3w forced-labor camp|Krych\u00f3w]]).{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|pp=159, 161}} Unusually, the deportees in the Lublin area were quickly able to establish contact with the Jews remaining in Slovakia, which led to [[Working Group (resistance organization)#Aid to deportees|extensive aid efforts]].{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=160}} However, the fate of the Jews deported from Slovakia was ultimately \"sealed within the framework of [[Operation Reinhard]]\" along with that of the Polish Jews, in the words of [[Yehoshua B\u00fcchler]].{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=153}}\n\n[[File:Alinas PL Maceba miejsce zamordowania 18400 zydow na MajdankuP5130085.jpg  |thumb|upright=|alt=Memorial plaque and trenches covered by grass|Trenches at [[Majdanek concentration camp|Majdanek]] where Jews were shot during [[Operation Harvest Festival]] on 3 November 1943.]]\nTransports went to Auschwitz after mid-June, where a minority of the victims were selected for labor and the remainder were killed in the [[gas chambers]].{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=326}}{{sfn| B\u00fcchler |1996|p=320}} This occurred for nine transports, the last of which arrived on 21 October 1942.{{sfn| B\u00fcchler |1996|p=320}}{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=181}} From 1 August to 18 September, no transports departed;{{sfn|Bauer |1994|p=96}}{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=181}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=320}} most of the Jews not exempt from deportation had already been deported or had fled to Hungary.{{sfn|Bauer |1994|pp=75, 97}} In mid-August, Tiso gave a [[Slovak, cast off your parasite|speech in Holi\u010d]] in which he described Jews as the \"eternal enemy\" and justified the deportations according to [[Christian ethics]].{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=8, 234}} Three more transports occurred in September and October 1942 before ceasing until 1944.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=8}}{{sfn|Fatran|2007|p=181}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1996|p=320}} By the end of 1942, only 500 or 600 Slovak Jews were still alive at Auschwitz.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=34}} Thousands of surviving Slovak Jews in the Lublin District were shot on 3\u20134 November 1943 during [[Operation Harvest Festival]].{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=34}}{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=160}} \n\nBetween 25 March and 20 October 1942, almost 58,000 Jews (two-thirds of the population) were deported.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=326}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=189}}{{sfn|Fatran|2007|pp=180\u2013181}} The exact number is unknown due to discrepancies in the sources.{{sfn|Silberklang|2013|pp=296\u2013297}} The deportations disproportionately affected poorer Jews from eastern Slovakia. Although the \u0160ari\u0161-Zempl\u00edn region in eastern Slovakia lost 85 to 90 percent of its Jewish population, \u017dilina reported that almost half of its Jews remained after the deportation.{{sfn|Ward|2002|p=584}}{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=187}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=233}} The deportees were held briefly in five camps in Slovakia before deportation;{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=66}} 26,384 from \u017dilina,{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=889}} 7,500 from Patr\u00f3nka,{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=855}} 7,000 from Poprad,{{sfn|Rajcan|2018|p=879}} 4,463 from Sere\u010f,{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=881}} and 4,000 to 5,000 from Nov\u00e1ky.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=874}} Nineteen trains went to Auschwitz, and another thirty-eight went to ghettos and concentration and extermination camps in the Lublin district.{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=151}} Only a few hundred survived the war,{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}} most at Auschwitz; almost no one survived in Lublin.{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=47}}\n\n=== Opposition, exemption, and evasion ===\n{{quotebox|align=right|width=18em|Everyone understands that the Holy See cannot stop Hitler. But who can understand that it does not know how to rein in a priest?|author=[[Domenico Tardini]], Vatican Undersecretary of State{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=232}}{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|pp=83\u201384}}}}\nThe Catholic Church opposed deportation, fearing that such actions from a Catholic government would discredit the church.{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|p=83}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=232}}  According to a SD ({{lang|de|[[Sicherheitsdienst]]}}) report, Giuseppe Burzio threatened Tiso with an [[interdict]].{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=232}} However, Slovak bishops were equivocal in their statement, endorsing [[Jewish deicide]] and other antisemitic myths while urging Catholics to treat Jews humanely.{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|p=82}} The Catholic Church ultimately chose not to discipline any of the Slovak Catholics who were complicit in the regime's actions.{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|p=84}} Officials from the \u00da\u017d{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p=167}} and several of the most influential Slovak rabbis sent petitions to Tiso, but he did not reply.{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|2014|pp=514\u2013515}}  Many Slovaks opposed the deportations,{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=38}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=69}}{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|p=83}} but this did not translate into action against them.{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|p=83}}{{sfn|L\u00f4n\u010d\u00edkov\u00e1|2017|p=91}} By March 1942, the [[Working Group (resistance organization)|Working Group]] (an underground organization which operated under the auspices of the \u00da\u017d) had formed to oppose the deportations. Its leaders, [[Zionism|Zionist]] organizer [[Gisi Fleischmann]] and Orthodox rabbi [[Michael Dov Weissmandl]], bribed [[Anton Va\u0161ek]], head of Department 14, and Wisliceny. It is unknown if the group's efforts had any connection with the halting of deportations.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=848}}{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=326}}{{sfn|Fatran|1994|loc=abstract}}\n\nMany Jews learned about the fate awaiting them during the first half of 1942, from various sources such as letters from deported Jews or escapees.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|pp=77\u201378}}{{sfn|Bauer|1994|pp=71\u201372}} Around 5,000 to 6,000 Jews fled to Hungary to avoid the deportations,{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=847}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2011b|p=110}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=70}} many by paying bribes{{sfn|Kamenec|2011b|p=110}} or with help from paid smugglers{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|p=62, Chapter IV ''passim''}} and [[Hashomer Hatzair]];{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=38}} about one third survived the war.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|p=187}}  Many owners of Aryanized businesses applied for work exemptions for the Jewish former owners. In some cases this was a fictitious Aryanization; other Aryanizers, motivated by profit, kept the Jewish former owners around for their skills.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|pp=62, 70}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|pp=176, 178}} About 2,000 Jews had false papers identifying themselves as Aryans.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=70}} Some Christian clergy baptized Jews, even those who were not sincere converts. Although conversion after 1939 did not exempt Jews from deportation,  being baptized made it easier to obtain other exemptions and some clergy edited records to predate baptisms.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|pp=279, 297}}{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|p=84}}\n\nAfter the deportations, between 22,000 and 25,000 Jews were still in Slovakia.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=40}}{{sfn|Ward|2002|p=589}} Some 16,000 Jews had exemptions; there were 4,217 converts to Christianity before 1939, at least 985 Jews in mixed marriages,{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=97}}{{sfn|Ward|2002|pp=587\u2013588}} and 9,687 holders of economic exemptions{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=97}} (particularly doctors, pharmacists, engineers, and agricultural experts, whose professions had shortages).{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=190}} One thousand Jews were protected by presidential exemptions, mostly in addition to other exemptions.{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=232\u2013233}}{{sfn|Ward|2002|pp=583, 587}} In addition to the exempted Jews, around 2,500 were interned in labor camps,{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=40}} and a thousand were serving in the Sixth Labor Battalion.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=38}}  When the deportations were halted, the government knew the whereabouts of only 2,500 Jews without exemptions.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=235}}\n\n==Hiatus (1943)==\nEnforcement of anti-Jewish laws lessened, and many Jews stopped wearing the yellow star.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=303}} Nevertheless, the remaining Jews \u2013 even those with exemptions \u2013 lived in constant fear of deportation.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=848}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|pp=283, 303}} The \u00da\u017d worked to improve conditions for laborers in the Slovak camps{{sfn|Rothkirchen|2001|p=599}}{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=848}} and to increase productivity, to strengthen the incentive to keep their workers in Slovakia.{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=190}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|pp=315\u2013316, 319}} In 1943, the labor camps earned 39 million Ks for the Slovak State.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2016|p=171}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=40}}{{efn|Equivalent to USD$975,000 at the time,{{sfn|Foreign Claims Settlement Commission|1968|p=655}} or ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|975,000 |1942|r=0}}}} today.{{sfn| Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis|2019}}}} The halt in deportations from Slovakia enabled the Working Group to launch the [[Europa Plan]], an unsuccessful effort to bribe SS chief [[Heinrich Himmler]] to spare the surviving Jews under German occupation.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=848}}{{sfn|Bauer|1994|pp=88\u201389, 99, Chapter 5\u20137 ''passim''}} It also smuggled aid to Jews in Poland,{{sfn|B\u00fcchler|1991|p=162}}{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p=178}}  and helped Polish Jews escape to Hungary via Slovakia.{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p=181}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2012|p=229}} In late April 1944 two Auschwitz escapees, [[Rudolf Vrba]] and [[Alfred Wetzler]], reached Slovakia.{{sfn|Bauer|2002|p=229}} The Working Group sent [[Vrba-Wetzler report|their report]] to Hungary and Switzerland; it reached the Western Allies in July.{{sfn|Bauer|2002|p=237}} \n\nAfter the [[Battle of Stalingrad]] and other reversals in the increasingly unpopular [[Eastern Front (World War II)|war in the east]], Slovak politicians realized that a German defeat was likely.{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=405}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=39}} Some HS\u013dS politicians (especially those in the radical faction) blamed economic setbacks on the Jews and agitated for the deportation of the remaining population.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|pp=280\u2013281}} On 7 February 1943, HS\u013dS radical Alexander Mach announced at a rally in [[Ru\u017eomberok]] that the transports would soon resume.{{sfn|Bauer|1994|p=86}} In early 1943, the Hlinka Guard and Department 14 prepared for the resumption of deportations: registering Jews, canceling economic exemptions, and hunting down Jews in hiding.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|pp=284\u2013285}} A plan to dispatch four trains between 18 and 22 April was not implemented.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=286}} In response to the threatened resumption, Slovak bishops issued a [[pastoral letter]] in Latin on 8 March condemning antisemitism and totalitarianism and defending the rights of all Jews.{{sfn|Kornberg|2015|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=Qo26CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA85 85]}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=236, 238}} Germany put increasing pressure on the Slovak State to hand over its remaining Jews in 1943 and 1944, but Slovak politicians did not agree to resume the deportations.{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=203}}\n\n[[File:May 1944 - Jews from Carpathian Ruthenia arrive at Auschwitz-Birkenau.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A large number of people, with their belongings, getting off a train|Jews from [[Carpathian Ruthenia]] arrive at Auschwitz, May 1944]]\nIn late 1943, leading army officers and [[intelligentsia]] formed the [[Slovak National Council]] to plan an insurrection against the regime;{{sfn|Kamenec|2011a|p=192}} other anti-fascists retreated to the [[Western Carpathians|Carpathian]] mountains and formed [[Slovak partisan|partisan]] groups.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=42}}{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=99}} Preparations for the uprising evoked mixed feelings in the remaining Slovak Jews, who feared that an uprising would bring about a crackdown on their community.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=99}} Underground groups organized at Sere\u010f{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=882}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=41}} and Nov\u00e1ky.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=876}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=41}} Slovak authorities began to re-register Jews in January 1944, prompting some to flee to Hungary.{{sfn|Fatran|1994|p=188}} On 19 March 1944 [[Operation Margarethe|Germany invaded Hungary]], including Carpathian Ruthenia and the areas ceded by Slovakia in 1938.{{sfn|Bauer|2002|p=226}}{{sfn|United States Holocaust Memorial Museum}} The Slovak Jews who had fled to Hungary tried to return, but many were arrested at the border and deported.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=99}} The Slovak ambassador in Budapest, [[J\u00e1n Spi\u0161iak]], issued documents to 3,000 Jews allowing them to legally cross the border,{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=42}} bringing the total Jewish population to 25,000.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=99}} Between 14 May and 7 July 437,000 Jews were deported from Hungary, most to Auschwitz;{{sfn|Longerich|2010|p=408}} including many Slovak Jews in the country.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=42}}  To counter the perceived security threat of Jews in the \u0160ari\u0161-Zempl\u00edn region with the front line moving westward, on 15 May 1944 the Slovak government ordered Jews to move to the western part of the country.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=113}}\n{{clear}}\n\n== {{anchor|Resumption of deportations}}Resumption of deportations (1944\u20131945) ==\n=== German invasion ===\n[[File:Karte Slowakischer Nationalaufstand 1944 - Aufstandsbeginn.png|thumb|upright=1.5|alt= Map showing the situation in the first days of the Slovak National Uprising.| Situation during the first days of the [[Slovak National Uprising]]]]\nConcerned about the increase in resistance, Germany invaded Slovakia; this precipitated the [[Slovak National Uprising]], which broke out on 29 August 1944.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=849}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=585}}{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|2014|p=515}} The insurgent forces seized central Slovakia but were defeated on 27 October at [[Bansk\u00e1 Bystrica]]. Partisans withdrew to the mountains and continued their [[guerrilla warfare|guerrilla campaign]] into 1945.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=849}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=249\u2013250, 252}} A new government was sworn in, with Jozef Tiso's cousin [[\u0160tefan Tiso|\u0160tefan]] as prime minister; Jozef remained president.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=43}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=249}} Burzio met with Tiso on 22 and 29 September, reportedly calling Tiso a liar when the president denied knowledge of deportations.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=251}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=85\u201386}} Pius XII instructed Burzio to tell Tiso that the Vatican condemned the persecution of individuals for their race or nationality.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=86}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=45}} The United States and Switzerland issued formal protests against the deportation of Jews.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=85\u201386}} Slovak propaganda blamed the Jews and [[Persecution of Czechs in the Slovak State|Czechs]] for the uprising.{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|2014|pp=517}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=84}} Nevertheless, the Slovak government preferred the concentration of Jews in concentration camps in Slovakia to their deportation.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=84}} Tiso asked for the Germans to spare at least baptized Jews and those in mixed marriages, but the Slovak exceptions were not honored by the Germans.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=251}}\n\nThe uprising provided the Germans with an opportunity to implement the Final Solution in Slovakia.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=82}} Anti-Jewish actions were nominally controlled by the Slovak State Ministry of Defense, but in practice the Germans dictated policy.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=43}}{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=101}}  Unlike the deportations of 1942, the roundups of Jews were organized and carried out by German forces.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=82}} [[Einsatzgruppe H]], commanded by SS officer {{ill|Josef Witiska|de||fr||sv}}, was formed to suppress the uprising immediately after it began and round up Jews and Romani people.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=101}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=587}} Local collaborators, including {{lang|de|[[SS-Heimatschutz Slowakei|SS-Heimatschutz]]}} (HS), {{lang|de|Freiwillige Schutzstaffel}} and the [[Hlinka Guard Emergency Divisions]] (POHG),{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=101}}{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=42}} were essential to Einsatzgruppe H's work.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=101}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=592}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=73}} Collaborators denounced those in hiding, impersonated partisans, and aided with interrogations.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=592}}\n\n[[File:Stanislav Rejthar 06.jpg|thumb|upright=1.1|left|alt=Group of soldiers in a hilly forest|[[Slovak partisans]] during the uprising]]\nAfter the uprising began, thousands of Jews fled to the mountainous interior and partisan-controlled areas around Bansk\u00e1 Bystrica,{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=99}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=42}} including many who left the labor camps after the guards fled.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|pp=100\u2013101}}  Around 1,600 to  2,000 Jews fought as partisans, ten percent of the total insurgent force,{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|2014|p=516}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=42}} although many hid their identity due to antisemitism in the partisan movement.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=119}}  Anti-Jewish legislation in the liberated areas was canceled by the Slovak National Council,{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=42}} but the attitude of the local population varied: some risked their lives to hide Jews, and others turned them in to the police.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=590}} Unlike in 1942, the death penalty was in effect for rescuers;{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=44}}   the majority provided help for a fee, although there were also cases of selfless rescues.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=45}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|pp=76\u201377}} Many Jews spent six to eight months in makeshift shelters or bunkers in the mountains,{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=590}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=44}} while others hid in the houses of non-Jews. Regardless, Jews required money for six to eight months of living expenses and the help of non-Jews willing to provide assistance.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|pp=104\u2013105}} Some of the Jews in shelters had to return home later in the winter, risking capture, because of the hunger and cold.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=105}}{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=44}} Living openly and continuing to work under false papers was typically only possible in Bratislava.{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=52}}\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Roundups ===\nJews who were captured were briefly imprisoned at local prisons or the Einsatzgruppe H office in Bratislava, from which they were sent to Sere\u010f for deportation. Local authorities provided lists of Jews, and many local residents also denounced Jews.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=590}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=93}}{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=52}}  In the first half of September there were large-scale raids in [[Topo\u013e\u010dany]] (3 September), [[Tren\u010d\u00edn]], and [[Nitra]] (7 September), during which 616 Jews were arrested and imprisoned in Ilava and Sere\u010f.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=43}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=88}} In \u017dilina, Einsatzgruppe 13 and collaborators arrested hundreds of Jews over the night of 13/14 September. The victims were deported to Sere\u010f or Ilava and thence to Auschwitz, where most were murdered.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=43}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=88\u201389}} Einsatzgruppe H reported that some Jews were able to escape because of insufficient personnel, but that both Germans and Slovaks generally supported the roundups and helped track down evaders.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=90}} After the defeat of the uprising, the German forces also hunted the Jews hiding in the mountains.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=92\u201393}}{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=52}} Although the bulk of arrests occurred during the first two months of occupation, the hunt for the Jews continued until 30 March 1945, when a Jewish prisoner was taken to Sere\u010f just three days before the camp was liberated.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=590}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=99\u2013100}}\n\n{{quotebox|quote=Half of Bratislava was on its feet this morning to watch the show of the {{lang|de|Judenevakuierung}} ... so was the kick, administered by an S.S.-man to a tardy Jew received by the large crowd ... with hand claps and cries of support and encouragement.|source=29 September [[Sicherheitsdienst|SD]] report{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=90}}{{sfn|Aronson|2004|p=177}}|width=22em }}\nIn Bratislava, some Jews were arrested by 20 September. However, the largest roundup was carried out in Bratislava during the night of 28/29 September by [[Einsatzkommando 29]], aided by 600 HS and POHG collaborators and a Luftwaffe unit that guarded the streets: around 1,600 Jews were arrested and taken to Sere\u010f.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=89}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=73}}{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|p=53}}\nThe United States embassy organized protection for some 300 Jews with foreign citizenship, housing them in a castle in [[Marianka]]. Brunner raided the castle on 11&nbsp;October; all but three of the prisoners were taken to Sere\u010f and deported to Auschwitz on 17 October.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=112}}{{sfn|Hlavinka|2018|p=871}} In mid-October, an office was established at the former Jewish Center to hunt down Jews in hiding, which tortured captured Jews into revealing the names and addresses of other Jews.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=93}} The one to two thousand Jews left in Bratislava were ordered to turn themselves in on 20 November or face imprisonment, but few did so.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=91\u201392}} Half of the Jews arrested after 19 November were in Bratislava, most in hiding with false papers.{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|pp=52, 211}} Henri Dunand of the [[International Committee of the Red Cross|Red Cross]] provided funding for a clandestine group led by Arnold Lazar, which provided money, food, and clothing to Jews in hiding in Bratislava.{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=45}}\n\n===Deportation===\n{{further |List of Holocaust transports from Slovakia#1944}} \n[[File:Birkenau Jewish mothers and their children walking to the gas chambers.jpg|thumb|Jewish women and children from [[Carpathian Ruthenia]] walking towards the gas chambers]]\nSere\u010f concentration camp was the primary facility for interning Jews prior to their deportation. Although there were no transports until the end of September, the Jews experienced harsh treatment (including rape and murder) and severe overcrowding as the population swelled to 3,000 \u2013 more than twice the intended capacity.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=882}}{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=102}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=96\u201397, 99}} SS officer [[Alois Brunner]], who had participated in the organization of transports of Jews from France and Greece,{{sfn|Longerich|2010|pp=391, 395, 403}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=74}} took over the camp's administration at the end of September.{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=74}} About 11,700 people were deported on eleven transports;{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|Rajcan|Hlavinka|2018|p=882}}{{sfn|Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd|2014|p=74}} the first five (from 30 September to 17 October) went to Auschwitz, where most of the victims were gassed. The final transport to Auschwitz, on 2 November, arrived after the gas chambers were shut down. Later transports left for [[Sachsenhausen concentration camp|Sachsenhausen]], [[Bergen-Belsen]], [[Ravensbr\u00fcck]], and [[Theresienstadt Ghetto|Theresienstadt]].{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=44}}{{sfn|Put\u00edk|2015|pp=54, 68\u201369}} \n\nTwo small transports left [[\u010cadca]] for Auschwitz on 1 and 5 September; Fatran estimates that the total number of deportees was about 400. In September and October, at least 131 people were deported from Slovakia via [[Zakopane]]; two of the transports ended at [[Krak\u00f3w-P\u0142asz\u00f3w concentration camp|Krak\u00f3w-P\u0142asz\u00f3w]] and the third at Auschwitz. A transport from [[Pre\u0161ov]], departing 26 November, ended up at Ravensbr\u00fcck. According to a Czechoslovak criminal investigation, another 800 Jews were deported in two transports from eastern Slovakia on 16 October and 16 December. Details on the transports leaving from locations other than Sere\u010f is fragmentary,{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=104}} and the total number of deportees is not known.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=82}} Slovak historian [[Ivan Kamenec]] estimated that 13,500 Jews were deported in 1944 and 1945, of whom 10,000 died,{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=849}}{{sfn|Kamenec|2007|p=337}}{{sfn|Ward|2002|p=589}} but Israeli historian Gila Fatran and Czech historian [[Lenka \u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1]] consider that 14,150 deportees can be verified and the true figure may be higher.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=82}}{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=119}} The Slovak regime also transferred several hundred political prisoners to German custody. Deported to [[Mauthausen concentration camp]], many died there.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=256}}\n\n=== Massacres ===\n{{further|Kremni\u010dka and Nemeck\u00e1 massacres}}\n[[File:Nemecka10Slovakia3.JPG|thumb|left|alt=spiral shaped memorial|Memorial to the victims of the Slovak National Uprising in [[Nemeck\u00e1]]]]\nAfter the German invasion, about 4,000 people were murdered in Slovakia, mostly by Einsatzgruppe H, but with help from local collaborators.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=105\u2013106}} About half (2,000) of the victims were Jews;{{sfn|Hutzelmann|2018|p=44}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=253}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=106}} other victims included partisans, supporters of the uprising, and Romani people.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=105}} One of the first executions occurred in the [[Topo\u013e\u010dany]] district, where Einsatzkommando 14 began its mass roundups of Jews. Many of the arrested Jews were taken to Sere\u010f for deportation, but 53 were shot in [[Nem\u010dice]] on 11 September.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|pp=107\u2013108}} The largest execution was in [[Kremni\u010dka and Nemeck\u00e1 massacres|Kremni\u010dka]], a small village {{convert|6|km}} away from Bansk\u00e1 Bystrica. Upon the capture of the rebel stronghold, Jews, partisans, Romanis, and others arrested in the area were held in the prison in the town. Of these, 743 people were brought to Kremni\u010dka for execution in a series of massacres between November and March, by Einsatzgruppe H and the POHG. Victims included 280 women and 99 children; half were Jewish. Hundreds of people were murdered at the nearby village of [[Kremni\u010dka and Nemeck\u00e1 massacres#Nemeck\u00e1|Nemeck\u00e1]], where the victims' bodies were burned after they were shot.{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013b|p=592}}{{sfn|\u0160indel\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1|2013a|p=115}}  [[Zvolen]]'s Jewish cemetery was used as an execution site; 218 bodies were exhumed after the end of the war.{{sfn|Fatran|1996|p=115}} \n{{clear}}\n\n== Aftermath ==\n{{see also|Postwar anti-Jewish violence in Slovakia}}\n[[File:KZ Sere\u010f - Holocaust-Museum - Namen der Ermordeten 2.jpg|thumb|Names of murdered Jews at the former [[Sere\u010f concentration camp]]]]\nThe [[Red Army]] captured Slovakia by the end of April 1945.{{sfn|Cichopek|2014|p=31}} Around 69,000 Jews, 77 percent of the prewar population, had been murdered.{{sfn|Cichopek-Gajraj|2014|p=52}}{{sfn|Cichopek|2014|p=19}} In addition to the 10,000{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|2014|p=518}} to 11,000 Jews who survived in Slovakia, 9,000 Jews returned who had been deported to concentration camps or fled abroad, and 10,000 Jews survived in the annexed territories. By the end of 1945, 33,000 Jews were living in Slovakia. Many survivors had lost their entire families, and a third suffered from [[tuberculosis]].{{sfn|Cichopek-Gajraj|2014|p=52}} Although a postwar Czechoslovak law negated property transactions arising from Nazi persecution, the autonomous Slovak government refused to apply it.{{sfn|Bazyler et al.|2019|p=402}}{{sfn|Cichopek|2014|p=94}} Heirless property was nationalized in 1947 into the Currency Liquidation Fund.{{sfn|Bazyler et al.|2019|p=402}} Those who had stolen Jewish property were reluctant to return it; former resistance members had also appropriated some stolen property. Conflict over restitution led to [[Postwar anti-Jewish violence in Slovakia| intimidation and violent attacks]], including the September 1945 [[Topo\u013e\u010dany pogrom]] and the [[Partisan Congress riots]] in August 1946.{{sfn|Cichopek|2014|pp=104\u2013105, 111\u2013112, 118\u2013119, 127\u2013129}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2013|pp=556\u2013557}}  Polish historian [[Anna Cichopek]] estimates that at least 36 Jews were murdered and more than 100 injured in postwar violence.{{sfn|Cichopek|2014|p=117}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2018|p=15}}\n\nTiso (who had fled to Austria) was extradited to Czechoslovakia, convicted of treason and collaboration, sentenced to death on 15 April 1947, and executed three days later.{{sfn|Rajcan|Vadkerty|Hlavinka|2018|p=849}} According to the court, his \"most immoral, most unchristian, and most inhuman\" action was ordering the deportation of the Slovak Jews.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=265}} Other perpetrators, including Tuka, were also tried, convicted, and executed.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=262}}{{sfn|Fedor\u010d\u00e1k|2015|p=42}}  Both Tiso and Tuka were tried under [[wikisource:sk:Nariadenie Slovenskej n\u00e1rodnej rady \u010d. 33 zo d\u0148a 15. m\u00e1ja 1945 o potrestan\u00ed fa\u0161istick\u00fdch zlo\u010dincov, okupantov, zradcov a kolaborantov a o zriaden\u00ed \u013eudov\u00e9ho s\u00fadnictva|Decree 33/1945]], an {{lang|la|[[ex post facto]]}} law that mandated the death penalty for the suppression of the Slovak National Uprising.{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=258, 263}}{{sfn|Fedor\u010d\u00e1k|2015|p=41}} In the cases of Tuka and Tiso, their roles in the Holocaust were a subset of the crimes for which they were convicted.{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=265}}{{sfn|Fedor\u010d\u00e1k|2015|p=44}} The authors of some of the more egregious antisemitic articles and caricatures were prosecuted after the war.{{sfn|L\u00f4n\u010d\u00edkov\u00e1|2017|p=86}} The trials painted Slovak State officials as traitors, thereby exonerating Slovak society from [[responsibility for the Holocaust]].{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=262}} \n\nThe Czechoslovak government supported Zionism, insisting that Jews assimilate into Czechoslovak culture or [[aliyah|emigrate to Palestine]].{{sfn|L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek|2013|p=51}} Jews who had declared German or Hungarian nationality on a prewar census were [[Bene\u0161 decrees|stripped of their citizenship]], losing any right to restitution, and were threatened with deportation.{{sfn|Cichopek|2014|pp=165\u2013166, 169}}  Most Jews in Slovakia emigrated to Israel or other countries in the years after the war. Emigration accelerated in 1948 after the [[1948 Czechoslovak coup d'\u00e9tat|Communist coup]] and nationalization of many businesses after the war. The number of Jewish communities decreased from 126 to 25, while the population decreased by 80%. Only a few thousand Jews were left by the end of 1949.{{sfn|Cichopek|2014|pp=228\u2013230}} Many of those who chose to stay changed their surnames and abandoned religious practice in order to fit in with the Slovak middle class.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2018|p=15}} As of 2019, the Jewish population is estimated at 2,000{{sfn|Bazyler et al.|2019|p=402}} to 3,000.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2018|p=17}}\n\n=={{anchor|Reception}}Legacy==\n[[File:Bratislava Holocaust Mahnmal 1289 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left |Holocaust Memorial at Rybn\u00e9 n\u00e1mestie in Bratislava]]\nThe [[Soviet anti-Zionism|government's attitude to Jews and Zionism]] shifted after 1948, leading to the 1952 [[Sl\u00e1nsk\u00fd trial]] in which the Czechoslovak government accused fourteen Communists (eleven of them Jewish) of belonging to a Zionist conspiracy.{{sfn|Sniegon|2014|p=61}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2018|pp=15\u201316}} Political censorship hampered the study of the Holocaust, and memorials to the victims of fascism did not mention Jews. In the 1960s, which were characterized by a liberalization known as the [[Prague Spring]], discussion of the Holocaust opened up.{{sfn|Sniegon|2014|pp=58, 62}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2013|p=558}} The [[Academy Award]]-winning 1965 film, ''[[The Shop on Main Street]]'', focused on Slovak culpability for the Holocaust.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2013|p=558}}{{sfn|Sniegon|2014|p=67}} Following the 1968 [[Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia]], authorities [[normalization (Czechoslovakia)|cracked down]]  on free expression,{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=269}}{{sfn|Sniegon|2014|pp=69\u201370}} \nwhile  anti-Zionist propaganda, much of it imported from the Soviet Union, intensified and veered into antisemitism after Israeli victory in the 1967 [[Six-Day War]].{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek|2018|pp=[https://books.google.com/books?id=7HtTDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA222 217\u2013218]}}\n\nAfter the [[Velvet Revolution|fall of the Communist regime]] in 1989, the Slovak government viewed remembering the Holocaust as a way of demonstrating the country's European identity before it [[2004 enlargement of the European Union|joined the European Union]] in 2004.{{sfn|Sniegon|2014|pp=73, 166}} Memorials were constructed in many Slovak cities during the 1990s to commemorate Holocaust victims,{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2013|p=574}}{{sfn|Sniegon|2014|pp=89\u201390}} and in October 2001 Slovakia designated 9 September (the anniversary of the passage of the Jewish Code) as Holocaust Victims and Racial Hatred Day.{{efn|{{lang-sk|Pam\u00e4tn\u00fd de\u0148 obet\u00ed holokaustu a rasov\u00e9ho n\u00e1silia}}{{sfn|Slovensk\u00e9 n\u00e1rodn\u00e9 m\u00fazeum|2018}}}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2013|p=575}} The [[National Memory Institute (Slovakia)|National Memory Institute]] was established in 2002 to provide access to the records of both the Slovak State and Communist state.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1 |2013|pp=564\u2013565}}  The post-Communist government enacted various laws for the restitution of Jewish property, but residency and citizenship requirements prevented emigrants from filing claims.{{sfn|Bazyler et al.|2019|pp=401\u2013402}} In 2002, ten percent of the value of the nationalized heirless property was released into a fund that paid for Jewish education and Holocaust memorials.{{sfn|Bazyler et al.|2019|p=411}} {{As of|January 2019}}, [[Yad Vashem]] (the official Israeli memorial to the Holocaust) had recognized 602 Slovaks as [[Righteous Among the Nations]] for risking their lives to save Jews.{{sfn|Yad Vashem|2019}} \n\nHolocaust relativism in Slovakia tends to manifest as attempts to deflect the blame for it onto Germans and Jews.{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|2014|p=506}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2018|p=10}} A 1997 textbook by [[Milan Stanislav \u010eurica]] and endorsed by the government sparked international controversy (and was eventually withdrawn from circulation) because it portrayed Jews as living happily in labor camps during the war.{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2013|pp=566\u2013467}}{{sfn|Ward|2013|p=277}}{{sfn|Sniegon|2014|p=209}} Jozef Tiso and the Slovak State have been the focus of Catholic and [[Ultranationalism|ultranationalist]] commemorations.{{sfn|Ward|2013|pp=276, 278}}{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2018|p=11}} The [[neo-Nazi]]{{sfn|Kub\u00e1tov\u00e1|L\u00e1n\u00ed\u010dek|2017|p=3}} [[Kotleba \u2013 People's Party Our Slovakia|Kotleba]] party, which is represented in the national parliament and the [[European Parliament]] and is especially popular with younger voters,{{sfn|Spectator|2019}} promotes a positive view of the Slovak State. Its leader, [[Marian Kotleba]], once described Jews as \"devils in human skin\".{{sfn|Paulovi\u010dov\u00e1|2018|pp=17, 20}} Members of the party have been charged with [[Holocaust denial]],{{sfn|Spectator|2016}}{{sfn|Spectator|2017}} which has been a criminal offense since 2001.{{sfn|Spectator|2016}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n==== Books ====\n{{refbegin|35em|indent=yes}}\n:{{cite book |last1=Aronson |first1=Shlomo|authorlink=Shlomo Aronson (historian) |title=Hitler, the Allies, and the Jews |date=2004 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |location=Cambridge |isbn=978-0-511-51183-7|ref=harv |language=en }}\n: {{cite book |last1=Bauer |first1=Yehuda |authorlink=Yehuda Bauer |title=Jews for Sale?: Nazi-Jewish Negotiations, 1933\u20131945 |date=1994 |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |isbn=978-0-300-05913-7 |ref=harv |language=en |location=New Haven |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/jewsforsalenazij00baue }}\n: {{cite book |last1=Bauer |first1=Yehuda |title=Rethinking the Holocaust |date=2002 |publisher=Yale University Press |isbn=978-0-300-09300-1 |ref=harv |language=en |location=New Haven }}\n:{{cite book |last1=Cichopek |first1=Anna |title=Beyond Violence: Jewish Survivors in Poland and Slovakia, 1944\u201348|title-link=Beyond Violence: Jewish Survivors in Poland and Slovakia, 1944\u201348 |date=2014 |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-03666-6 |ref=harv |language=en}}\n:{{cite book |last1=De\u00e1k |first1=Istv\u00e1n |authorlink1=Istv\u00e1n De\u00e1k |title=Europe on Trial: The Story of Collaboration, Resistance, and Retribution during World War II |date=2015 |orig-year=2013|publisher=[[Routledge]] |location=London |isbn=978-0-8133-4790-5 |ref=harv |language=en}}\n:{{cite book |last1=Fatran |first1=Gila |title=Boj o pre\u017eitie|trans-title=The Struggle for Survival |date=2007 |publisher=SNM - M\u00fazeum \u017didovskej Kult\u00fary |location=Bratislava |isbn=978-80-8060-206-2 |ref=harv |language=sk}}\n:{{cite book |author1=Foreign Claims Settlement Commission |title=Foreign Claims Sett