Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos |volume=3 |title=Camps and Ghettos under European Regimes Aligned with Nazi Germany |isbn=978-0-253-02373-5|location=Bloomington |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |ref=harv |date=2018|pp=854\u2013855}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia |last1=Hlavinka |first1=J\u00e1n |entry=Marianka|editor1-last=Megargee|editor1-first=Geoffrey P. |editor2-last=White|editor2-first=Joseph R.|editor3-last=Hecker|editor3-first=Mel |series=Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos |volume=3 |title=Camps and Ghettos under European Regimes Aligned with Nazi Germany |isbn=978-0-253-02373-5|location=Bloomington |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |ref=harv |date=2018|p=871}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia|last1=Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd |first1=Eduard |last2=Rajcan |first2=Vanda  |first3=J\u00e1n |last3=Hlavinka |entry=Nov\u00e1ky|editor1-last=Megargee|editor1-first=Geoffrey P. |editor2-last=White|editor2-first=Joseph R.|editor3-last=Hecker|editor3-first=Mel |series=Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos |volume=3 |title=Camps and Ghettos under European Regimes Aligned with Nazi Germany |isbn=978-0-253-02373-5|location=Bloomington |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |ref=harv |date=2018|pp=874\u2013877|translator-last=Kramarikova|translator-first=Marianna}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia  |last1=Rajcan |first1=Vanda |entry=Poprad|editor1-last=Megargee|editor1-first=Geoffrey P. |editor2-last=White|editor2-first=Joseph R.|editor3-last=Hecker|editor3-first=Mel |series=Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos |volume=3 |title=Camps and Ghettos under European Regimes Aligned with Nazi Germany |isbn=978-0-253-02373-5|location=Bloomington |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |ref=harv |date=2018|pp=878\u2013880}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia|last1=Ni\u017e\u0148ansk\u00fd |first1=Eduard |last2=Rajcan |first2=Vanda  |first3=J\u00e1n |last3=Hlavinka |entry=Sere\u010f|editor1-last=Megargee|editor1-first=Geoffrey P. |editor2-last=White|editor2-first=Joseph R.|editor3-last=Hecker|editor3-first=Mel |series=Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos |volume=3 |title=Camps and Ghettos under European Regimes Aligned with Nazi Germany |isbn=978-0-253-02373-5|location=Bloomington |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |ref=harv |date=2018|pp=881\u2013883|translator-last=Kramarikova|translator-first=Marianna}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia  |last1=Rajcan |first1=Vanda |entry=\u017dilina|editor1-last=Megargee|editor1-first=Geoffrey P. |editor2-last=White|editor2-first=Joseph R.|editor3-last=Hecker|editor3-first=Mel |series=Encyclopedia of Camps and Ghettos |volume=3 |title=Camps and Ghettos under European Regimes Aligned with Nazi Germany |isbn=978-0-253-02373-5|location=Bloomington |publisher=United States Holocaust Memorial Museum |ref=harv |date=2018|pp=889\u2013890}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==== Web ====\n{{refbegin|35em|indent=yes}}\n*{{cite web |last1=Bachn\u00e1r |first1=Alexander |title=Odtabuizovan\u00fd pr\u00e1por |url=https://www.holocaust.cz/zdroje/clanky-z-ros-chodese/ros-chodes-2002/zari-9/odtabuizovany-prapor/ |publisher=Terez\u00edn Initiative |accessdate=23 January 2019 |ref=harv |language=sk |date=7 August 2011|trans-title=Detached Battalion}}\n*{{cite web |title=Consumer Price Index, 1800\u2013 |url=https://www.minneapolisfed.org/about-us/monetary-policy/inflation-calculator/consumer-price-index-1800- |publisher=Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis |accessdate=29 November 2019 |ref={{sfnref|Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis|2019}}}}\n*{{cite news |title=Mazurek not prosecuted for Holocaust denial |url=https://spectator.sme.sk/c/20266405/mazurek-not-prosecuted-for-holocaust-denial.html |accessdate=16 January 2019 |work=The Slovak Spectator |date=7 September 2016 |language=en|ref={{sfnref|Spectator|2016}}}}\n*{{cite news |title=Extremist charged with Holocaust denial |url=https://spectator.sme.sk/c/20617009/extremist-charged-with-holocaust-denial.html |accessdate=16 January 2019 |work=The Slovak Spectator |date=2 August 2017 |language=en|ref={{sfnref|Spectator|2017}}}}\n*{{cite news |title=Under 30s would vote far-right Kotleba the next PM |url=https://spectator.sme.sk/c/22271423/under-30s-would-vote-far-right-kotleba-the-next-pm.html |accessdate=5 January 2020 |work=The Slovak Spectator |date=28 November 2019 |ref={{sfnref|Spectator|2019}} |language=en}}\n*{{cite web |title=Pam\u00e4tn\u00fd de\u0148 obet\u00ed holokaustu a rasov\u00e9ho n\u00e1silia 2018 |url=http://www.snm.sk/?muzeum-holokaustu-podujatia&clanok=pamatny-den-obeti-holokaustu-a-rasoveho-nasilia-2018-1 |publisher=Slovensk\u00e9 n\u00e1rodn\u00e9 m\u00fazeum |accessdate=28 September 2018 |ref={{sfnref|Slovensk\u00e9 n\u00e1rodn\u00e9 m\u00fazeum|2018}} |language=sk |date=7 September 2018|trans-title=Holocaust Victims and Racial Hatred Day 2018}}\n*{{cite web |title=Names of Righteous by Country |url=https://www.yadvashem.org/righteous/statistics.html |publisher=Yad Vashem |accessdate=28 November 2019 |language=en |ref={{sfnref|Yad Vashem|2019}}}}\n*{{cite web |title=The Holocaust in Subcarpathian Rus and Southern Slovakia |url=https://encyclopedia.ushmm.org/content/en/article/the-holocaust-in-subcarpathian-rus-and-southern-slovakia |website=Holocaust Encyclopedia |publisher=[[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]] |accessdate=8 February 2020 |ref={{sfnref|United States Holocaust Memorial Museum}} |language=en}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Holocaust}}\n{{Holocaust Slovakia}}\n{{Czechoslovakia in World War II}}\n{{Slovak People's Party}}\n\n[[Category:Jewish Slovak history]]\n[[Category:The Holocaust by country]]\n[[Category:Antisemitism in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Slovakia during World War II]]\n[[Category:Murder in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:1940s murders in Europe]]\n[[Category:1940s in Slovakia]]\n[[Category:Germany\u2013Slovakia relations]]\n", "name_user": "Gog the Mild", "label": "safe", "comment": "circa", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Holocaust_in_Slovakia"}
{"title_page": "Targum Sheni", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}{{Rabbinical Literature}}\nThe '''''Targum Sheni''''' (''\"Second Targum\"'') is an [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] translation (''[[targum]]'') and elaboration of the [[Book of Esther]], that embellishes the Biblical account with considerable new [[apocrypha]]l material, not on the face of it directly related to the [[Esther]] story.\n\n== Differences from the Book of Esther ==\nThe ''[[Jewish Encyclopedia]]'' characterizes the story as a \"genuine and exuberant [[midrash]]\",<ref>\"[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=483&letter=E&search=targum%20sheni#1 Esther]\", ''[[Jewish Encyclopedia]]'', 1906</ref> i.e. a free elaboration, of a kind not unusual in [[Rabbinic literature]].\n\nOne notable addition to the story involves King [[Solomon]] holding a feast for the daunting army of animals, birds and demonic spirits he has as subjects. But the [[woodcock]] refuses to attend, on the grounds that Solomon is inferior to the [[Queen of Sheba]] to King [[Solomon]]. Solomon sends for the Queen, and houses her in a room made of glass, through which he reveals that she has a hairy foot. She demands from him the answer to three riddles before she will pay homage:<ref name=\"Lassner1993\">Jacob Lassner, ''Demonizing the Queen of Sheba: Boundaries of Gender and Culture in Postbiblical Judaism and Medieval Islam''. University of Chicago Press, 1993, pp.14-17</ref>\n* A cistern of wood; buckets of water; they draw up stones; they cause water to flow. \u2014 A tube of cosmetic eye-paint.\n* What is the thing which comes as dust from the earth, easts dust, is poured out as water, and sticks to the house? \u2014 [[Naphtha]].\n* What is that which acts as an oracle (or as a storm), goes at the head of all, cries loudly and bitterly with its head bowed down like a rush, is a cause of praise to the free, of shame to the poor, of honour to the dead, of disgrace to the living, of joy to the birds, and of grief to the fish? \u2014 [[Flax]].\nSolomon solves the riddles, and the two exchange gifts. The riddles are noteworthy examples of [[Hebrew Riddles]].<ref>Christine Goldberg, ''Turandot's Sisters: A Study of the Folktale AT 851'', Garland Folklore Library, 7 (New York: Garland, 1993), pp. 22-23.</ref>\n\n== Date ==\nThere is controversy among scholars about the date of the Targum Sheni. Various 19th-century scholars dated it to the 4th century (S. Gelbhaus), 6th century (P. Cassel), or 11th century (L. Munk).<ref name=\"ej\">Encyclopaedia Judaica, [https://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/targum-sheni Targum Sheni]</ref> The ''Encyclopaedia Judaica'' argued for a dating of the late 7th or early 8th century.<ref name=\"ej\"/> Linguistic features of the (Galilean) Aramaic text, including its many Greek loan words, are one of the stronger arguments in support of an earlier dating. More recently Allegra Iafrate (2015) argued for a date in the 10th century due to the fact that Targum Sheni shows dependency on and shares striking similarities with [[De Ceremoniis]], a work which itself was composed in the middle of the 10th century in the [[Byzantine Empire]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Iafrate|first=Allegra|title=The Wandering Throne of Solomon: Objects and Tales of Kingship in the Medieval Mediterranean (Mediterranean Art Histories: Studies in Visual Cultures, Late Antiquity to the Modern Period, Band 2)|publisher=Brill|year=2015|isbn=9004305181|location=|pages=147-151}}</ref>\n\nThere are a number of notable parallels between the ''Targum Sheni'' account and the [[Qur'an]]ic account of Solomon and the Queen in [[Sura]] 27 (and also some notable differences), and much of the controversy centers on whether these similarities support an earlier or later dating, that is, which composition exerted influence on the other. The ascribed date of 800 by the ''[[Encyclopaedia Judaica]]'' is post-Islamic so the ''Targum Sheni'' may have been influenced by the Qur'an. However, some scholars believe that the Qur'anic account islamicises pre-existing Jewish and [[folklore|folkloric]] traditions, perhaps including sixth-century Christian input, which were closer to those presented in the ''Targum Sheni''.<ref>cf Lassner, p. 227 n.2 and pp. 132 et seq</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==See also==\n*[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/14248-targum#anchor12 Apocryphal Additions to Esther - Jewish Encyclopedia]\n*[https://archive.org/details/explanatorycomme00cassrich An explanatory commentary on Esther] tr. of Cassel, Paulus, Edinburgh 1888. Translation of Targum Sheni in appendix I\n\n[[Category:Midrashim]]\n[[Category:Targums]]\n[[Category:Book of Esther]]\n[[Category:Oral Torah]]\n\n\n{{Judaism-book-stub}}\n{{Hebrew-Bible-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}{{Rabbinical Literature}}\nThe '''''Targum Sheni''''' (''\"Second Targum\"'') is an [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] translation (''[[targum]]'') and elaboration of the [[Book of Esther]], that embellishes the Biblical account with considerable new [[apocrypha]]l material, not on the face of it directly related to the [[Esther]] story.\n\n== Differences from the Book of Esther ==\nThe ''[[Jewish Encyclopedia]]'' characterizes the story as a \"genuine and exuberant [[midrash]]\",<ref>\"[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=483&letter=E&search=targum%20sheni#1 Esther]\", ''[[Jewish Encyclopedia]]'', 1906</ref> i.e. a free elaboration, of a kind not unusual in [[Rabbinic literature]].\n\nOne notable addition to the story involves King [[Solomon]] holding a feast for the daunting army of animals, birds and demonic spirits he has as subjects. But the [[woodcock]] refuses to attend, on the grounds that Solomon is inferior to the [[Queen of Sheba]] to King [[Solomon]]. Solomon sends for the Queen, and houses her in a room made of glass, through which he reveals that she has a hairy foot. She demands from him the answer to three riddles before she will pay homage:<ref name=\"Lassner1993\">Jacob Lassner, ''Demonizing the Queen of Sheba: Boundaries of Gender and Culture in Postbiblical Judaism and Medieval Islam''. University of Chicago Press, 1993, pp.14-17</ref>\n* A cistern of wood; buckets of water; they draw up stones; they cause water to flow. \u2014 A tube of cosmetic eye-paint.\n* What is the thing which comes as dust from the earth, easts dust, is poured out as water, and sticks to the house? \u2014 [[Naphtha]].\n* What is that which acts as an oracle (or as a storm), goes at the head of all, cries loudly and bitterly with its head bowed down like a rush, is a cause of praise to the free, of shame to the poor, of honour to the dead, of disgrace to the living, of joy to the birds, and of grief to the fish? \u2014 [[Flax]].\nSolomon solves the riddles, and the two exchange gifts. The riddles are noteworthy examples of [[Hebrew Riddles]].<ref>Christine Goldberg, ''Turandot's Sisters: A Study of the Folktale AT 851'', Garland Folklore Library, 7 (New York: Garland, 1993), pp. 22-23.</ref>\n\n== Date ==\nThere is controversy among scholars about the date of the Targum Sheni. Various 19th-century scholars dated it to the 4th century (S. Gelbhaus), 6th century (P. Cassel), or 11th century (L. Munk).<ref name=\"ej\">Encyclopaedia Judaica, [https://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/targum-sheni Targum Sheni]</ref> The ''Encyclopaedia Judaica'' argued for a dating of the late 7th or early 8th century.<ref name=\"ej\"/> Linguistic features of the (Galilean) Aramaic text, including its many Greek loan words, are one of the stronger arguments in support of an earlier dating. More recently Allegra Iafrate (2015) argued for a date in the 10th century due to the fact that the Targum Sheni shows dependency on and shares striking similarities with [[De Ceremoniis]], a work which itself was composed in the middle of the 10th century in the [[Byzantine Empire]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Iafrate|first=Allegra|title=The Wandering Throne of Solomon: Objects and Tales of Kingship in the Medieval Mediterranean (Mediterranean Art Histories: Studies in Visual Cultures, Late Antiquity to the Modern Period, Band 2)|publisher=Brill|year=2015|isbn=9004305181|location=|pages=147-151}}</ref>\n\nThere are a number of notable parallels between the ''Targum Sheni'' account and the [[Qur'an]]ic account of Solomon and the Queen in [[Sura]] 27 (and also some notable differences), and much of the controversy centers on whether these similarities support an earlier or later dating, that is, which composition exerted influence on the other. The ascribed date of 800 by the ''[[Encyclopaedia Judaica]]'' is post-Islamic so the ''Targum Sheni'' may have been influenced by the Qur'an. However, some scholars believe that the Qur'anic account islamicises pre-existing Jewish and [[folklore|folkloric]] traditions, perhaps including sixth-century Christian input, which were closer to those presented in the ''Targum Sheni''.<ref>cf Lassner, p. 227 n.2 and pp. 132 et seq</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==See also==\n*[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/14248-targum#anchor12 Apocryphal Additions to Esther - Jewish Encyclopedia]\n*[https://archive.org/details/explanatorycomme00cassrich An explanatory commentary on Esther] tr. of Cassel, Paulus, Edinburgh 1888. Translation of Targum Sheni in appendix I\n\n[[Category:Midrashim]]\n[[Category:Targums]]\n[[Category:Book of Esther]]\n[[Category:Oral Torah]]\n\n\n{{Judaism-book-stub}}\n{{Hebrew-Bible-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WilliamOR81", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor edit. Gr.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Targum_Sheni"}
{"title_page": "Dileep", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian actor and film producer}}\n{{about|an Indian actor born in 1968|other uses}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Dileep\n| image        = Dileep 2016.jpg\n| caption      = Dileep in 2016\n| birth_name   = Gopalakrishnan Padmanabhan Pillai\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1968|10|27}}\n| birth_place  = [[Edavanakad]], Kerala, India\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| alma_mater   = [[Mahatma Gandhi University, Kottayam|Mahatma Gandhi University]]\n| occupation   = {{hlist|Actor|Film producer|Businessman}}\n| years_active = 1991\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{Plainlist|\n* {{marriage|[[Manju Warrier]]|1998|2015|reason=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|[[Kavya Madhavan]]|2016}}\n}}\n| awards       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Kerala State Film Awards]]\n* [[Filmfare Awards South]]\n}}\n}}\n'''Gopalakrishnan Padmanabhan Pillai''' (born 27 October 1968), better known by his stage name '''Dileep''', is an Indian actor, film producer and businessman, who predominantly works in the [[Malayalam cinema|Malayalam film industry]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://newsable.asianetnews.com/editorial/being-human-salmanification-of-janapriya-nayakan-dileep |title=The 'Being Human' Salmanification of 'Janapriya Nayakan' Dileep |work=Asianet News Network Pvt Ltd |access-date=24 August 2018}}</ref> He has acted in more than 150 films and has won several awards, including four [[Kerala State Film Awards]] and a [[Filmfare Awards South]].\n\nBeginning as an [[Impressionist (entertainment)|impressionist]] in stage shows, Dileep attained recognition after being cast on the television comedy series ''Comicola'' on [[Asianet (TV channel)|Asianet]] and its successor ''[[Cinemala]]''. Dileep with [[Nadirshah]] produced and performed in the audio cassette series ''De Maveli Kombathu'', a successful [[sketch comedy]], which later turned into a television series on Asianet. He began his film career as an [[assistant director]] and worked under director [[Kamal (director)|Kamal]] in nine films, beginning with ''[[Vishnulokam]]'' in 1991, and made his acting debut with a minor role in Kamal's ''[[Ennodu Ishtam Koodamo]]'' (1992). He acted in a principal role in the 1994 film ''[[Manathe Kottaram]]'' taking the screen name Dileep. He established himself as a successful actor during late 1990s, mostly playing comedic roles.\n\nThe box office success of the 2002 film ''[[Meesa Madhavan]]'' significantly raised his stardom in Malayalam cinema, the film also won him the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor \u2013 Malayalam]]. In the same year, he won the [[Kerala State Film Award - Special Jury Award]] for ''[[Kunjikoonan (2002 film)|Kunjikoonan]]'', and in 2005, a [[Kerala State Film Award - Special Mention|Special Mention]] for his gender-disputed role in ''[[Chanthupottu]]''. In 2003, Dileep founded the film production company [[Graand Production]], its debut film was ''[[C.I.D. Moosa]]''. His 2004 production ''[[Kathavasheshan]]'' won the [[Kerala State Film Award for Second Best Film]]. In 2008, he produced ''[[Twenty:20 (film)|Twenty:20]]'' to raise funds for the [[Association of Malayalam Movie Artists]] (AMMA). The film starred almost all actors in the guild and became the highest-grossing Malayalam film up until then.\n\nIn 2011, his role in ''[[Vellaripravinte Changathi]]'' won him his first [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actor]]. His 2015 comedy ''[[Two Countries]]'' and 2017 political thriller ''[[Ramaleela]]'' grossed over {{INR}} 50&nbsp;crore ({{INR}} 500&nbsp;million) each and were ranked among the [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|top ten highest-grossing Malayalam films]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/worldwide-box-office-collection-dileep-mamta-mohandas-two-countries-enters-rs-50-crore-club-666243 |title=Worldwide box office collection Dileep-Mamta Mohandas Two countries enters Rs 50 crore club |website=ibtimes.co.in}}</ref> Beside films, Dileep owns the [[Multiplex (movie theater)|multiplex theatre]] D Cinemaas and the [[restaurant chain]] Dhe Puttu. Dileep was married to actress [[Manju Warrier]] from 1998 to 2015. He married actress [[Kavya Madhavan]] in 2016.\n\n==Early life==\n\nDileep was born in [[Edavanakad]], in [[Ernakulam district]] of [[Kerala]], India to Padmanabhan Pillai and Sarojam. He is the eldest among three children.<ref name=\"movies.deepthi.com\">{{cite web |url=http://movies.deepthi.com/malayalam/actors/dileep.html |title=Dileep \u2013 Malayalam celebrities the stories and the gossips |website=movies.deepthi.com}}</ref> He has a brother, Anoop, and a sister, Sabitha.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0d24\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d19\u0d4d\u0d19\u0d33\u0d41\u0d1f\u0d46 \u0d35\u0d4b\u0d1f\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d41 \u0d06\u0d7c\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4a\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d46? |url=http://www.manoramaonline.com/movies/movie-news/star-vote-kerala.html |publisher=manoramaonline.com |accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref> He studied at [[Vidyadhiraja Vidya Bhavan Higher Secondary School]] in Aluva, where he passed the tenth standard in 1985, and joined [[Union Christian College, Aluva]] for pre-degree (higher secondary) third group, during 1985\u20131987. Later, he pursued a degree in history from [[Maharaja's College, Ernakulam]].<ref name=\"metromatinee1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metromatinee.com/artist/Dileep-28 |title=Dileep:Profile And Biography, Malayalam Movie Actor Dileep latest Photo Gallery &#124; Video Gallery, Malayalam Movie Actor Dileep, Dileep Filimography, Dileep Films and Cinemas, Dileep Awards And Nominations |publisher=Metromatinee.com |date=7 February 1968 |accessdate=20 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131008113131/http://www.metromatinee.com/artist/Dileep-28 |archivedate=8 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zonkerala.com/achievers/article.php?id=8 |title=Dileep \u2013 Career, productions, latest movies and awards by actor Dileep Photos |publisher=Zonkerala.com |date=27 October 1967 |accessdate=20 October 2013}}</ref> It was during his time in Maharaja's College that he began taking [[Impressionist (entertainment)|impressionist]] acts (mimicry) seriously.<ref name=\"metromatinee1\"/> Dileep along with his friend [[Nadirshah]] produced and performed (voice) in the [[Onam]]-based audio cassette (album) titled ''De Maveli Kombathu'', which helped his entry into the film industry.<ref>{{cite news |title=An Onam sans Dileep: Mollywood stares at another first |url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/entertainment/entertainment-news/2017/08/29/dileep-no-onam-malayalam-movies-high-court-bail.html |accessdate=6 February 2019 |work=[[Malayala Manorama]] |date=29 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career ==\n{{multiple issues|section=yes\n|{{BLP sources section|date=August 2018}}\n{{example farm|section|date=August 2018}}\n}}\n\n===1991\u20131999: Early years===\nDileep started his career at [[Kalabhavan]], working as a [[Impressionist (entertainment)|mimicry]] artist in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nostalgia grips Dileep fans as buddy Nadirshah shares old photo |url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/entertainment/entertainment-news/2019/01/30/dileep-nadirshah-challenge-old-photo-facebook.html |accessdate=6 February 2019 |work=OnManorama}}</ref> He also performed in [[Asianet (TV channel)|Asianet]]'s comedy show ''Comicola''. Later, he served as the [[assistant director]] to the Indian film director, [[Kamal (director)|Kamal]]. While being an assistant director, Dileep acted in a few small roles, debuting with a small scene in [[Kamal (director)|Kamal]]'s ''[[Ennodu Ishtam Koodamo]]'' (1992). Kamal recommended his name to many directors. The film ''[[Manathe Kottaram]]'' (1994), directed by Sunil, gave him his first break in the role of Dileep, through which he gained his screen name. Other minor roles during this time included [[Joshiy|Joshi]]'s ''Sainyam'' (1993), [[Sibi Malayil]]'s ''Sindoora Rekha'' (1995), Viji Thampi's ''Pidakozhi Koovunna Nootand'' (1994), Kamal's ''[[Ulladakkam]]'' (1993) and ''Sudhinam'' (1994), ''Thooval Kottaram'' (1996), ''Swapna Lokathe Balabhaskaran'' (1996), and ''[[Ee Puzhayum Kadannu]]'' (1996). He played a supporting role in [[I. V. Sasi]]'s ''Varnapakittu'' (1997). ''Punjabi House'' (1998) led to the beginning of the popular Dileep-Harishri Asokan combo.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n===2000\u20132009: Stardom===\nIn 2000, Dileep starred in the films ''[[Mister Butler]]'' (2000), ''[[Darling Darling (2000 film)|Darling Darling]]'' (2000) and ''[[Joker (2000 film)|Joker]]'' (2000). He played a supporting role in ''[[Thenkasipattanam]]'' in 2000,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ibtimes.co.in/kavya-madhavans-8-best-movies-she-celebrates-25th-anniversary-industry-666327 |title=Kavya Madhavan's 8 best movies as she celebrates 25th anniversary in industry |last=James |first=Anu |work=International Business Times, India Edition |access-date=24 August 2018}}</ref> and also appeared in ''Ee Parakkum Thalika'' (2001), ''[[Ishtam (2001 Malayalam film)|Ishtam]]'' (2001), and ''[[Mazhathullikkilukkam]]'' (2002).\n\nIn 2002 he won the [[Kerala State Film Award|Kerala State Film Special Jury Award]] for playing the role of Kunjan in the film ''[[Kunjikoonan (2002 film)|Kunjikoonan]]''.  In [[Lal Jose]]'s ''[[Meesa Madhavan]]'' (2002), Dileep played the role of the thief Madhavan, that same year he also debuted in [[Tamil cinema]] with ''[[Raajjiyam]]''.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}} His next appearances were in the films ''Kalyanaraman'' (2003), [[Jayaraj]]'s ''[[Thilakkam]]'' (2003), and [[Johny Antony]]'s ''[[C.I.D. Moosa]]'' (2003) He also produced and starred in [[T. V. Chandran]]'s ''Kadhavaseshan'' (2004). In 2004, he starred in [[Priyadarshan]]'s ''[[Vettam]]''. ''[[Chanthupottu]]'' (2005) saw his reunion with Lal Jose. He won a [[Kerala State Film Award \u2013 Special Mention|Special Mention]] at the [[Kerala State Film Awards]] for his performance in the movie.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.filmibeat.com/celebs/dileep-malayalam-actor/awards.html |title=Dileep (Malayalam Actor) Awards & Nominations List |website=FilmiBeat  |access-date=4 June 2019}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} He ventured into action with Joshy{{'}}s ''Runway'' (2004). ''[[Kochi Rajavu]]'' (2005), was his next release. His next releases were ''Chess'' (2006) and ''Don'' (2006). Also in 2006, he lent his voice to the character played by [[Shahid Kapoor]] in Priyadarshan's Hindi film [[Chup Chup Ke]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/dileep-is-also-a-dubbing-artist-malayalam-news-22346 |title=IndiaGlitz \u2013 Dileep is also a dubbing artist \u2013 Malayalam Movie News }}</ref> The story of the 2006 movie ''[[Pachakuthira]]'' was written by Dileep.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.msidb.org/displayProfile.php?category=story&artist=Dileep |title=Profile of Malayalam Story Writer Dileep |website=en.msidb.org}}</ref> His second film with the director [[Sathyan Anthikad]], ''Vinodayathra'', was released in April 2007. The same year, he played the athlete Arjun in ''[[Speed Track (film)|Speed Track]]'', the debut of director Jayasurya. He then appeared in [[Blessy]]'s ''[[Calcutta News]]'' (2008).\n\nDileep produced [[Joshiy]]-directed ''[[Twenty:20 (film)|Twenty:20]]'' (2008) to raise funds for the [[Association of Malayalam Movie Artists]] (AMMA). The film starred became the highest-grossing Malayalam film ({{INR}} 31.4 crore) until that time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nair |first=Manoj |title=Malayalam movies: Non-linear narratives are making the box-office ring louder |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/business-of-bollywood/malayalam-movies-non-linear-narratives-are-making-the-box-office-ring-louder/articleshow/8478136.cms |accessdate=5 February 2019 |work=[[The Economic Times]] |date=21 May 2011}}</ref> In 2009, his films included ''[[Crazy Gopalan]] and'' ''[[Moz & Cat]]'' directed by director [[Fazil (director)|Fazil]]. Dileep's performance in the 2009 movie ''[[Passenger (2009 film)|Passenger]]'' was well received.{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}} He ended the decade with ''[[Swantham Lekhakan]]'' which saw him team up with Indian actress ''[[Gopika]].''\n\n===2010\u2013present===\nIn the beginning of the 2010s, Dileep starred in ''[[Bodyguard (2010 film)|Bodyguard]]'' directed by ''[[Siddique (director)|Siddique]]''. The film had multiple remakes including ''[[Kaavalan]]'' starring ''[[Vijay (actor)|Vijay]],'' and ''[[Bodyguard (2011 Hindi film)|Bodyguard]],'' starring ''[[Salman Khan]]''. ''Aagathan'' and ''[[Paappi Appacha]]'' were his next films. His production venture ''[[Malarvaadi Arts Club]]'' was directed by [[Vineeth Sreenivasan]] which was also the debut vehicle of ''[[Nivin Pauly]]''. The Hindi children's movie ''Toofan'' was released in 2010, directed by [[Major Ravi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metromatinee.com/movies/index.php?FilmID=3176-Toofan |title=Toofan Hindi movie |work=Metromatinee |access-date=19 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016041042/http://www.metromatinee.com/movies/index.php?FilmID=3176-Toofan#Synopsis |archive-date=16 October 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2010, he also starred in his 100th movie{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}, ''[[Kaaryasthan]]''. In 2011, he appeared in ''[[Christian Brothers (film)|Christian Brothers]]'', ''[[China Town (2011 film)|China Town]]'', ''[[Orma Mathram]]'', ''[[The Filmstaar]]'' and ''[[Vellaripravinte Changathi]],'' for which he won a [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/regional/have-portrayed-role-of-ill-fated-actor-truthfully-dileep-247495 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140727041542/http://movies.ndtv.com/regional/have-portrayed-role-of-ill-fated-actor-truthfully-dileep-247495 |url-status=dead |title=Have portrayed role of ill-fated actor truthfully: Dileep \u2013 NDTV |date=27 July 2014 |archivedate=27 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\nHis first release in 2012 was ''[[Spanish Masala]] ''directed by [[Lal Jose]]. His next movie in 2012 was ''[[Mayamohini]].'' His first release in 2013 was ''[[Proprietors: Kammath & Kammath]]''. He played the lead role in [[Vysakh]]'s ''[[Sound Thoma]]'' and later starred in [[Sringaravelan]]. In 2014 was he appeared in Rafi's ''[[Ring Master]].'' He also appeared in ''[[Avatharam (2014 Malayalam film)|Avatharam]]'' and ''[[Villali Veeran]]''. In 2015 he starred in'' [[Ivan Maryadaraman]]'', a remake of ''[[Maryada Ramanna]]''. He also did a guest appearance in ''[[Shivrajkumar]]'' 's''[[Vajrakaya]]''. He played the title character in Jeethu Joseph's ''[[Life of Josutty]]''. \"[[Two Countries]]\" released on Christmas Day 2015, directed by Shafi, became the highest-grossing film in his career.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}} In 2016, his first film was \"[[King Liar]]\". Later he starred in ''Welcome to Central Jail'', and ''Pinneyum,'' with veteran director ''[[Adoor Gopalakrishnan]]''. His 2017 film, [[Ramaleela]], became one of the highest-grossing Malayalam films of all time.{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}} His first movie release of 2018 was ''[[Kammara Sambhavam|Kammarasambhavam]]'', in which he played negative role for first time and it co-starred South Indian actor [[Siddharth (actor)|Siddharth]]. In 2019, his first movie release was [[Kodathi Samaksham Balan Vakeel]] which was commercial success at the box office. \n\n==Personal life==\nDileep married [[Manju Warrier]] on 20 October 1998.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com\">{{cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/dileep-warrier-kavya-madhavan-wedding-watch-video-see-pics-4394125/ |title=Dileep and Kavya Madhavan get married in a private ceremony, watch video and pics |date=25 November 2016 }}</ref> They have a daughter Meenakshi (born in 2000). In July 2014, the couple filed for divorce which was granted on 31 January 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/contentView.do?contentType=EDITORIAL&programId=11565555&contentId=16199995&tabId=1 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140514220535/http://english.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/contentView.do?contentType=EDITORIAL&programId=11565555&contentId=16199995&tabId=1 |url-status=dead |title=Manorama Online \u2013 Dileep-Manju to part ways |date=14 May 2014 |archivedate=14 May 2014 }}</ref> \nOn 25 November 2016, Dileep married actress [[Kavya Madhavan]] with whom he had been rumoured to be in a relationship for a long time.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.manoramaonline.com/news/kerala/2017/08/03/manju-warrier-not-dileep-first-wife-kavya-madhavan.html |title=Marital maze: Manju Warrier was not Dileep's first wife, say TV reports |work=The Malayala Manorama |date=8 August 2017 |accessdate=3 August 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/malayalam/dileep-kavya-madhavan-expecting-first-child-5343723/ Dileep and Kavya Madhavan expecting their first child]. The Indian Express (6 September 2018). Retrieved 21 September 2018.</ref> The couple have a daughter Mahalakshmi, born in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/malayalam/dileep-kavya-madhavan-baby-girl-5408443/ |title=Kavya Madhavan and Dileep welcome a baby girl |date=19 October 2018 |work=The Indian Express |access-date=20 November 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Off-screen work===\nBesides acting and film production, Dileep is also involved in film [[Film distribution|distribution]] (through [[Graand Production]]) and [[Movie theater|exhibition]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}} He owns the [[Multiplex (movie theater)|multiplex theater]] complex D Cinemaas situated in [[Chalakudy]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}} He along with his friend [[Nadirshah]] founded the [[restaurant chain]] Dhe Puttu, they have restaurants in [[Kochi]], [[Kozhikode]], [[Qatar]] and [[Dubai]], as of 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=James |first=Anu |title=Dileep to get his passport back; actor to visit Dubai for Dhe Puttu launch |url=https://www.ibtimes.co.in/dileep-get-his-passport-back-actor-visit-dubai-dhe-puttu-launch-750211 |accessdate=6 February 2019 |work=[[International Business Times]] |date=21 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Abduction and sexual assault case===\n\nOn 28 June 2017, Dileep was interrogated by the [[Kerala Police]] in connection with the abduction and [[sexual assault]] of a popular actress.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/thiruvananthapuram/actress-abduction-case-dileep-to-become-prime-accused/articleshow/61155047.cms |title=Actress abduction case: Dileep to become prime accused |website=The Times of India |access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manoramaonline.com/news/latest-news/2017/07/01/actress-attack-case-police-raid-in-kavya-madhavan-s-online-textile-shop-office.html |title=Attack on Actress: search on Kavya Madhavan's textile showroom |work=Malayala Manorama |date=1 July 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kochi/sit-questions-kavya-madhavan/articleshow/59762348.cms |title=Actor rape case: SIT questions Kavya Madhavan |work=The Times of India |date=26 July 2017 |accessdate=26 July 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/regional-cinema/story/dileep-reinstated-in-amma-mohanlal-parvathy-bhavana-revathy-padmapriya-1272307-2018-06-28 Mollywood has set a horrible example by supporting Dileep \u2013 Movies News]. ''India Today''.in (28 June 2018). Retrieved 21 September 2018.</ref> On 10 July 2017, Dileep was arrested by [[Kerala Police]] for alleged conspiracy, and was remanded by the court.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/dileep-arrested-live-updates-actress-abduction-case-4744501/ |title=Kerala actor Dileep arrested on conspiracy charge in actress attack |date=11 July 2017 |work=The Indian Express}}</ref> On 3 October 2017, he was released on conditional bail by the [[Kerala High Court]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/actor-dileep-granted-bail-in-sexual-assault-case/article19790330.ece |title=Dileep granted bail in woman actor sexual assault case |first=K. c |last=Gopakumar |date=3 October 2017 |work=The Hindu}}</ref> In June 2018, he filed a petition in the Kerala High Court charging the Kerala Police of deliberately framing him. He requested the case be handed over to the [[Central Bureau of Investigation]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.india.com/showbiz/malayalam-actress-molestation-case-trial-begins-against-dileep-and-others-2943933/ |title=Dileep Appears in Court As Trial Begins in the Malayalam Actress Molestation Case |last=India |first=Press Trust of |date=14 March 2018 |work=India.com |access-date=24 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tactics-delay-trial-dileep-seeks-cbi-probe-malayalam-actor-abduction-case-82974 |title=Tactics to delay trial? Dileep seeks CBI probe in Malayalam actor abduction case |date=13 June 2018 |work=The News Minute |access-date=24 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his arrest, Dileep's membership was revoked by various film organisations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kochi/actor-dileep-expelled-from-amma-after-his-arrest/articleshow/59546651.cms |title=Actor Dileep expelled from AMMA after his arrest |work=The Times of India |date=11 July 2017 |accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref> Several political parties protested against Dileep and his business firms were vandalised, including Dhe Puttu restaurant and the [[Multiplex (movie theater)|multiplex theatre]] D Cinemaas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/110717/mob-turns-violent-dileeps-business-firms-attacked.html |title=Mob turns violent, Dileep's business firms attacked |work=Deccan Chronicle |date=21 July 2017 |accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref> Dileep in the major prosecution process has filed an additional plea for accessing video footage of the incident. The plea was denied both the Angamaly Magistrate Court and Kerala High Court denied the plea. Mukul Rohatgi, a former [[Attorney General of India]] represented him in the case. In April 2019, the [[Government of Kerala]] froze charges against him until the court has given an independent verdict on the case.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/2017/jul/10/here-is-a-timeline-of-events-in-the-malayalam-actress-abduction-case-1626830.html |title=Here is a timeline of events in the Kerala actress abduction case |work=The New Indian Express |accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/news/kerala/2019/04/09/malayalam-superstar-dileep-actress-abduction-case.html |title=Malayalam superstar Dileep gets relief in abduction case &#124; English Manorama |publisher=English.manoramaonline.com |date=9 April 2019 |accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref> Mukul Rhotagi was able to get him a stay on the trial from Supreme Court thus making the case inactive until Dileep gets access to the video.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/india/malayalam-superstar-dileep-gets-relief-in-actress-kidnap-and-assault-case-1.1556902506786 |title=Malayalam superstar Dileep gets relief in actress kidnap and assault case |work=Gulf News |accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|Dileep filmography}}\n\n===Playback singing===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Song !! Film !! Year !! Lyrics !! Composer\n|-\n|\"Theme Music\"||''[[Chandranudikkunna Dikhil]]''|| 1999 || S. Ramesan Nair ||[[Vidyasagar (composer)|Vidhyasagar]]\n|- \n|\"Onnaam Malakeri\"|| ''[[Kalyanaraman (2002 film)|Kalyanaraman]]''|| 2002 || [[Kaithapram Damodaran]] || [[Berny-Ignatius]]\n|-\n|\"Saare Saare\" || ''[[Thilakkam]]'' || 2003 || Kaithapram Damodaran ||[[Kaithapram Damodaran]]\n|-\n| \"Manmadanalle\" || \"[[Inspector Garud]]\" ||2007 || ||[[Alex Paul]]\n|-\n|\"Kandaal Njaanoru\" || ''[[Sound Thoma]]'' || 2013 || [[Nadirshah]] ||[[Gopi Sunder]]\n|-\n|\"Ashakoshale Pennundo\" || ''[[Sringaravelan]]'' || 2013 || Nadirshah || \n|}\n\n==Awards==\n;[[Kerala State Film Awards]]\n* 2011: [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] \u2013 ''[[Vellaripravinte Changathi]]''\n* 2005: [[Kerala State Film Award \u2013 Special Mention|Special Mention]] \u2013 ''[[Chanthupottu]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.in.msn.com/movies/features/gallery.aspx?cp-documentid=3664894&page=14 |title=Dileep: 'Chanthupottu' \u2013 Malayalam Actor of the Decade |publisher=MSN |date=26 February 2010 |accessdate=20 October 2013 }}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* 2004: [[Kerala State Film Award for Second Best Film|Second Best Film]] \u2013 ''[[Kathavasheshan]]'' (producer)\n* 2002: [[Kerala State Film Award (Special Jury Award)|Special Jury Award]] \u2013 ''[[Kunjikoonan (2002 film)|Kunjikoonan]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.in.msn.com/southcinemathisdecade/malayalamactor/gallery.aspx?cp-documentid=3664894&page=13 |title=Dileep: 'Kunjikoonan' \u2013 Malayalam Actor of the Decade |publisher=MSN |date=26 February 2010 |accessdate=20 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100306130131/http://entertainment.in.msn.com/southcinemathisdecade/malayalamactor/gallery.aspx?cp-documentid=3664894&page=13 |archive-date=6 March 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n;\n;[[Filmfare Awards South]]\n* 2002: [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor \u2013 Malayalam|Best Actor in Malayalam]] \u2013 ''[[Meesha Madhavan]]''\n\n;\n;[[Asianet Film Awards]]\n* 2002: Best Actor \u2013 ''[[Kunjikoonan (2002 film)|Kunjikoonan]]''\n* 2004: Special Jury Award \u2013 ''[[Kathavasheshan]]''\n* 2008: Best Film \u2013 ''[[Twenty:20 (film)|Twenty:20]]''\n* 2010: Most Popular Actor \u2013 ''Body Guard'' \n* 2013: Award of Excellence for completing 20 years in Malayalam film industry<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metromatinee.com/news-articles/16th-ujala-asianet-film-awards-2014-winners-list-7548 |title=16th Ujala Asianet Film Awards 2004 |work=Metromatinee |access-date=11 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517014018/http://www.metromatinee.com/news-articles/16th-ujala-asianet-film-awards-2014-winners-list-7548 |archive-date=17 May 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n;\n;[[Kerala Film Critics Association Awards]]\n* 2001: Best Supporting Actor-Joker\n* 2004: Best Actor \u2013 Kadhavaseshan\n* 2005: Best Actor \u2013 ''Chanthupottu''\n\n;\n;[[South Indian International Movie Awards]]\n* 2014: Best Actor \u2013 ''[[Sound Thoma]]''\n\n;\n;[[Vanitha Film Awards]]\n* 2013: Best Popular Actor\n\n; \n;Jaihind Film Awards\n\n* 2010: Most Popular Actor Award\n* 2011: Chalachitra Pratibha Award\n* 2012: Best Actor \u2013 ''[[Mayamohini]]'', ''Arike''\n* 2013: Most Popular Actor Award\n* 2014: Most Popular Actor Award\n\n;\n;Amrita Film Awards\n\n* 2008: Best Film \u2013 ''[[Twenty:20 (film)|Twenty:20]]''\n* 2010: Most Popular Actor Award\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Dileep}}\n* {{IMDb name|0226770|name=Dileep}}\n\n{{FilmfareMalayalamBestActor}}\n{{Kerala State Film Award for Best Actor}}\n{{SIIMA Award for Best Actor}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dileep}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Kochi]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Kochi]]\n[[Category:Filmfare Awards South winners]]\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Kerala State Film Award winners]]\n[[Category:Maharaja's College, Ernakulam alumni]]\n[[Category:Malayalam film producers]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Kochi]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Malayalam cinema]]\n[[Category:People from Aluva]]\n[[Category:SIIMA Awards winners]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian actor and film producer}}\n{{about|an Indian actor born in 1968|other uses}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Dileep\n| image        = Dileep 2016.jpg\n| caption      = Dileep in 2016\n| birth_name   = Gopalakrishnan Padmanabhan Pillai\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1968|10|27}}\n| birth_place  = [[Edavanakad]], Kerala, India\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  = \n| alma_mater   = [[Mahatma Gandhi University, Kottayam|Mahatma Gandhi University]]\n| occupation   = {{hlist|Actor|Film producer|Businessman}}\n| years_active = 1991\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{Plainlist|\n* {{marriage|[[Manju Warrier]]|1998|2015|reason=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|[[Kavya Madhavan]]|2016}}\n}}\n| awards       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Kerala State Film Awards]]\n* [[Filmfare Awards South]]\n}}\n}}\n'''Gopalakrishnan Padmanabhan Pillai''' (born 27 October 1968), better known by his stage name '''Dileep''', is an Indian actor, film producer and businessman, who predominantly works in the [[Malayalam cinema|Malayalam film industry]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://newsable.asianetnews.com/editorial/being-human-salmanification-of-janapriya-nayakan-dileep |title=The 'Being Human' Salmanification of 'Janapriya Nayakan' Dileep |work=Asianet News Network Pvt Ltd |access-date=24 August 2018}}</ref> He has acted in more than 150 films and has won several awards, including four [[Kerala State Film Awards]] and a [[Filmfare Awards South]].\n\nBeginning as an [[Impressionist (entertainment)|impressionist]] in stage shows, Dileep attained recognition after being cast on the television comedy series ''Comicola'' on [[Asianet (TV channel)|Asianet]] and its successor ''[[Cinemala]]''. Dileep with [[Nadirshah]] produced and performed in the audio cassette series ''De Maveli Kombathu'', a successful [[sketch comedy]], which later turned into a television series on Asianet. He began his film career as an [[assistant director]] and worked under director [[Kamal (director)|Kamal]] in nine films, beginning with ''[[Vishnulokam]]'' in 1991, and made his acting debut with a minor role in Kamal's ''[[Ennodu Ishtam Koodamo]]'' (1992). He acted in a principal role in the 1994 film ''[[Manathe Kottaram]]'' taking the screen name Dileep. He established himself as a successful actor during late 1990s, mostly playing comedic roles.\n\nThe box office success of the 2002 film ''[[Meesa Madhavan]]'' significantly raised his stardom in Malayalam cinema, the film also won him the [[Filmfare Award for Best Actor \u2013 Malayalam]]. In the same year, he won the [[Kerala State Film Award - Special Jury Award]] for ''[[Kunjikoonan (2002 film)|Kunjikoonan]]'', and in 2005, a [[Kerala State Film Award - Special Mention|Special Mention]] for his gender-disputed role in ''[[Chanthupottu]]''. In 2003, Dileep founded the film production company [[Graand Production]], its debut film was ''[[C.I.D. Moosa]]''. His 2004 production ''[[Kathavasheshan]]'' won the [[Kerala State Film Award for Second Best Film]]. In 2008, he produced ''[[Twenty:20 (film)|Twenty:20]]'' to raise funds for the [[Association of Malayalam Movie Artists]] (AMMA). The film starred almost all actors in the guild and became the highest-grossing Malayalam film up until then.\n\nIn 2011, his role in ''[[Vellaripravinte Changathi]]'' won him his first [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actor]]. His 2015 comedy ''[[Two Countries]]'' and 2017 political thriller ''[[Ramaleela]]'' grossed over {{INR}} 50&nbsp;crore ({{INR}} 500&nbsp;million) each and were ranked among the [[List of highest-grossing Indian films|top ten highest-grossing Malayalam films]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/worldwide-box-office-collection-dileep-mamta-mohandas-two-countries-enters-rs-50-crore-club-666243 |title=Worldwide box office collection Dileep-Mamta Mohandas Two countries enters Rs 50 crore club |website=ibtimes.co.in}}</ref> Beside films, Dileep owns the [[Multiplex (movie theater)|multiplex theatre]] D Cinemaas and the [[restaurant chain]] Dhe Puttu. Dileep was married to actress [[Manju Warrier]] from 1998 to 2015. He married actress [[Kavya Madhavan]] in 2016.\n\n==Early life==\n\nDileep was born in [[Edavanakad]], in [[Ernakulam district]] of [[Kerala]], India to Padmanabhan Pillai and Sarojam. He is the eldest among three children.<ref name=\"movies.deepthi.com\">{{cite web |url=http://movies.deepthi.com/malayalam/actors/dileep.html |title=Dileep \u2013 Malayalam celebrities the stories and the gossips |website=movies.deepthi.com}}</ref> He has a brother, Anoop, and a sister, Sabitha.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0d24\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d19\u0d4d\u0d19\u0d33\u0d41\u0d1f\u0d46 \u0d35\u0d4b\u0d1f\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d41 \u0d06\u0d7c\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4a\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d46? |url=http://www.manoramaonline.com/movies/movie-news/star-vote-kerala.html |publisher=manoramaonline.com |accessdate=17 May 2016}}</ref> He studied at [[Vidyadhiraja Vidya Bhavan Higher Secondary School]] in Aluva, where he passed the tenth standard in 1985, and joined [[Union Christian College, Aluva]] for pre-degree (higher secondary) third group, during 1985\u20131987. Later, he pursued a degree in history from [[Maharaja's College, Ernakulam]].<ref name=\"metromatinee1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metromatinee.com/artist/Dileep-28 |title=Dileep:Profile And Biography, Malayalam Movie Actor Dileep latest Photo Gallery &#124; Video Gallery, Malayalam Movie Actor Dileep, Dileep Filimography, Dileep Films and Cinemas, Dileep Awards And Nominations |publisher=Metromatinee.com |date=7 February 1968 |accessdate=20 October 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131008113131/http://www.metromatinee.com/artist/Dileep-28 |archivedate=8 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zonkerala.com/achievers/article.php?id=8 |title=Dileep \u2013 Career, productions, latest movies and awards by actor Dileep Photos |publisher=Zonkerala.com |date=27 October 1967 |accessdate=20 October 2013}}</ref> It was during his time in Maharaja's College that he began taking [[Impressionist (entertainment)|impressionist]] acts (mimicry) seriously.<ref name=\"metromatinee1\"/> Dileep along with his friend [[Nadirshah]] produced and performed (voice) in the [[Onam]]-based audio cassette (album) titled ''De Maveli Kombathu'', which helped his entry into the film industry.<ref>{{cite news |title=An Onam sans Dileep: Mollywood stares at another first |url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/entertainment/entertainment-news/2017/08/29/dileep-no-onam-malayalam-movies-high-court-bail.html |accessdate=6 February 2019 |work=[[Malayala Manorama]] |date=29 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career ==\n{{multiple issues|section=yes\n|{{BLP sources section|date=August 2018}}\n{{example farm|section|date=August 2018}}\n}}\n\n===1991\u20131999: Early years===\nDileep started his career at [[Kalabhavan]], working as a [[Impressionist (entertainment)|mimicry]] artist in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nostalgia grips Dileep fans as buddy Nadirshah shares old photo |url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/entertainment/entertainment-news/2019/01/30/dileep-nadirshah-challenge-old-photo-facebook.html |accessdate=6 February 2019 |work=OnManorama}}</ref> He also performed in [[Asianet (TV channel)|Asianet]]'s comedy show ''Comicola''. Later, he served as the [[assistant director]] to the Indian film director, [[Kamal (director)|Kamal]]. While being an assistant director, Dileep acted in a few small roles, debuting with a small scene in [[Kamal (director)|Kamal]]'s ''[[Ennodu Ishtam Koodamo]]'' (1992). Kamal recommended his name to many directors. The film ''[[Manathe Kottaram]]'' (1994), directed by Sunil, gave him his first break in the role of Dileep, through which he gained his screen name. Other minor roles during this time included [[Joshiy|Joshi]]'s ''Sainyam'' (1993), [[Sibi Malayil]]'s ''Sindoora Rekha'' (1995), Viji Thampi's ''Pidakozhi Koovunna Nootand'' (1994), Kamal's ''[[Ulladakkam]]'' (1993) and ''Sudhinam'' (1994), ''Thooval Kottaram'' (1996), ''Swapna Lokathe Balabhaskaran'' (1996), and ''[[Ee Puzhayum Kadannu]]'' (1996). He played a supporting role in [[I. V. Sasi]]'s ''Varnapakittu'' (1997). ''Punjabi House'' (1998) led to the beginning of the popular Dileep-Harishri Asokan combo.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}}\n\n===2000\u20132009: Stardom===\nIn 2000, Dileep starred in the films ''[[Mister Butler]]'' (2000), ''[[Darling Darling (2000 film)|Darling Darling]]'' (2000) and ''[[Joker (2000 film)|Joker]]'' (2000). He played a supporting role in ''[[Thenkasipattanam]]'' in 2000,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.ibtimes.co.in/kavya-madhavans-8-best-movies-she-celebrates-25th-anniversary-industry-666327 |title=Kavya Madhavan's 8 best movies as she celebrates 25th anniversary in industry |last=James |first=Anu |work=International Business Times, India Edition |access-date=24 August 2018}}</ref> and also appeared in ''Ee Parakkum Thalika'' (2001), ''[[Ishtam (2001 Malayalam film)|Ishtam]]'' (2001), and ''[[Mazhathullikkilukkam]]'' (2002).\n\nIn 2002 he won the [[Kerala State Film Award|Kerala State Film Special Jury Award]] for playing the role of Kunjan in the film ''[[Kunjikoonan (2002 film)|Kunjikoonan]]''.  In [[Lal Jose]]'s ''[[Meesa Madhavan]]'' (2002), Dileep played the role of the thief Madhavan, that same year he also debuted in [[Tamil cinema]] with ''[[Raajjiyam]]''.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}} His next appearances were in the films ''Kalyanaraman'' (2003), [[Jayaraj]]'s ''[[Thilakkam]]'' (2003), and [[Johny Antony]]'s ''[[C.I.D. Moosa]]'' (2003) He also produced and starred in [[T. V. Chandran]]'s ''Kadhavaseshan'' (2004). In 2004, he starred in [[Priyadarshan]]'s ''[[Vettam]]''. ''[[Chanthupottu]]'' (2005) saw his reunion with Lal Jose. He won a [[Kerala State Film Award \u2013 Special Mention|Special Mention]] at the [[Kerala State Film Awards]] for his performance in the movie.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.filmibeat.com/celebs/dileep-malayalam-actor/awards.html |title=Dileep (Malayalam Actor) Awards & Nominations List |website=FilmiBeat  |access-date=4 June 2019}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} He ventured into action with Joshy{{'}}s ''Runway'' (2004). ''[[Kochi Rajavu]]'' (2005), was his next release. His next releases were ''Chess'' (2006) and ''Don'' (2006). Also in 2006, he lent his voice to the character played by [[Shahid Kapoor]] in Priyadarshan's Hindi film [[Chup Chup Ke]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/dileep-is-also-a-dubbing-artist-malayalam-news-22346 |title=IndiaGlitz \u2013 Dileep is also a dubbing artist \u2013 Malayalam Movie News }}</ref> The story of the 2006 movie ''[[Pachakuthira]]'' was written by Dileep.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.msidb.org/displayProfile.php?category=story&artist=Dileep |title=Profile of Malayalam Story Writer Dileep |website=en.msidb.org}}</ref> His second film with the director [[Sathyan Anthikad]], ''Vinodayathra'', was released in April 2007. The same year, he played the athlete Arjun in ''[[Speed Track (film)|Speed Track]]'', the debut of director Jayasurya. He then appeared in [[Blessy]]'s ''[[Calcutta News]]'' (2008).\n\nDileep produced [[Joshiy]]-directed ''[[Twenty:20 (film)|Twenty:20]]'' (2008) to raise funds for the [[Association of Malayalam Movie Artists]] (AMMA). The film starred became the highest-grossing Malayalam film ({{INR}} 31.4 crore) until that time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Nair |first=Manoj |title=Malayalam movies: Non-linear narratives are making the box-office ring louder |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/business-of-bollywood/malayalam-movies-non-linear-narratives-are-making-the-box-office-ring-louder/articleshow/8478136.cms |accessdate=5 February 2019 |work=[[The Economic Times]] |date=21 May 2011}}</ref> In 2009, his films included ''[[Crazy Gopalan]] and'' ''[[Moz & Cat]]'' directed by director [[Fazil (director)|Fazil]]. Dileep's performance in the 2009 movie ''[[Passenger (2009 film)|Passenger]]'' was well received.{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}} He ended the decade with ''[[Swantham Lekhakan]]'' which saw him team up with Indian actress ''[[Gopika]].''\n\n===2010\u2013present===\nIn the beginning of the 2010s, Dileep starred in ''[[Bodyguard (2010 film)|Bodyguard]]'' directed by ''[[Siddique (director)|Siddique]]''. The film had multiple remakes including ''[[Kaavalan]]'' starring ''[[Vijay (actor)|Vijay]],'' and ''[[Bodyguard (2011 Hindi film)|Bodyguard]],'' starring ''[[Salman Khan]]''. ''Aagathan'' and ''[[Paappi Appacha]]'' were his next films. His production venture ''[[Malarvaadi Arts Club]]'' was directed by [[Vineeth Sreenivasan]] which was also the debut vehicle of ''[[Nivin Pauly]]''. The Hindi children's movie ''Toofan'' was released in 2010, directed by [[Major Ravi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metromatinee.com/movies/index.php?FilmID=3176-Toofan |title=Toofan Hindi movie |work=Metromatinee |access-date=19 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141016041042/http://www.metromatinee.com/movies/index.php?FilmID=3176-Toofan#Synopsis |archive-date=16 October 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2010, he also starred in his 100th movie{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}}, ''[[Kaaryasthan]]''. In 2011, he appeared in ''[[Christian Brothers (film)|Christian Brothers]]'', ''[[China Town (2011 film)|China Town]]'', ''[[Orma Mathram]]'', ''[[The Filmstaar]]'' and ''[[Vellaripravinte Changathi]],'' for which he won a [[Kerala State Film Award for Best Actor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://movies.ndtv.com/regional/have-portrayed-role-of-ill-fated-actor-truthfully-dileep-247495 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140727041542/http://movies.ndtv.com/regional/have-portrayed-role-of-ill-fated-actor-truthfully-dileep-247495 |url-status=dead |title=Have portrayed role of ill-fated actor truthfully: Dileep \u2013 NDTV |date=27 July 2014 |archivedate=27 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\nHis first release in 2012 was ''[[Spanish Masala]] ''directed by [[Lal Jose]]. His next movie in 2012 was ''[[Mayamohini]].'' His first release in 2013 was ''[[Proprietors: Kammath & Kammath]]''. He played the lead role in [[Vysakh]]'s ''[[Sound Thoma]]'' and later starred in [[Sringaravelan]]. In 2014 was he appeared in Rafi's ''[[Ring Master]].'' He also appeared in ''[[Avatharam (2014 Malayalam film)|Avatharam]]'' and ''[[Villali Veeran]]''. In 2015 he starred in'' [[Ivan Maryadaraman]]'', a remake of ''[[Maryada Ramanna]]''. He also did a guest appearance in ''[[Shivrajkumar]]'' 's''[[Vajrakaya]]''. He played the title character in Jeethu Joseph's ''[[Life of Josutty]]''. \"[[Two Countries]]\" released on Christmas Day 2015, directed by Shafi, became the highest-grossing film in his career.{{Citation needed|date=August 2018}} In 2016, his first film was \"[[King Liar]]\". Later he starred in ''Welcome to Central Jail'', and ''Pinneyum,'' with veteran director ''[[Adoor Gopalakrishnan]]''. His 2017 film, [[Ramaleela]], became one of the highest-grossing Malayalam films of all time.{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}} His first movie release of 2018 was ''[[Kammara Sambhavam|Kammarasambhavam]]'', in which he played negative role for first time and it co-starred South Indian actor [[Siddharth (actor)|Siddharth]].\n\n==Personal life==\nDileep married [[Manju Warrier]] on 20 October 1998.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com\">{{cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/regional/dileep-warrier-kavya-madhavan-wedding-watch-video-see-pics-4394125/ |title=Dileep and Kavya Madhavan get married in a private ceremony, watch video and pics |date=25 November 2016 }}</ref> They have a daughter Meenakshi (born in 2000). In July 2014, the couple filed for divorce which was granted on 31 January 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/contentView.do?contentType=EDITORIAL&programId=11565555&contentId=16199995&tabId=1 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140514220535/http://english.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/contentView.do?contentType=EDITORIAL&programId=11565555&contentId=16199995&tabId=1 |url-status=dead |title=Manorama Online \u2013 Dileep-Manju to part ways |date=14 May 2014 |archivedate=14 May 2014 }}</ref> \nOn 25 November 2016, Dileep married actress [[Kavya Madhavan]] with whom he had been rumoured to be in a relationship for a long time.<ref name=\"indianexpress.com\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.manoramaonline.com/news/kerala/2017/08/03/manju-warrier-not-dileep-first-wife-kavya-madhavan.html |title=Marital maze: Manju Warrier was not Dileep's first wife, say TV reports |work=The Malayala Manorama |date=8 August 2017 |accessdate=3 August 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/malayalam/dileep-kavya-madhavan-expecting-first-child-5343723/ Dileep and Kavya Madhavan expecting their first child]. The Indian Express (6 September 2018). Retrieved 21 September 2018.</ref> The couple have a daughter Mahalakshmi, born in 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/malayalam/dileep-kavya-madhavan-baby-girl-5408443/ |title=Kavya Madhavan and Dileep welcome a baby girl |date=19 October 2018 |work=The Indian Express |access-date=20 November 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Off-screen work===\nBesides acting and film production, Dileep is also involved in film [[Film distribution|distribution]] (through [[Graand Production]]) and [[Movie theater|exhibition]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}} He owns the [[Multiplex (movie theater)|multiplex theater]] complex D Cinemaas situated in [[Chalakudy]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2019}} He along with his friend [[Nadirshah]] founded the [[restaurant chain]] Dhe Puttu, they have restaurants in [[Kochi]], [[Kozhikode]], [[Qatar]] and [[Dubai]], as of 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=James |first=Anu |title=Dileep to get his passport back; actor to visit Dubai for Dhe Puttu launch |url=https://www.ibtimes.co.in/dileep-get-his-passport-back-actor-visit-dubai-dhe-puttu-launch-750211 |accessdate=6 February 2019 |work=[[International Business Times]] |date=21 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Abduction and sexual assault case===\n\nOn 28 June 2017, Dileep was interrogated by the [[Kerala Police]] in connection with the abduction and [[sexual assault]] of a popular actress.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/thiruvananthapuram/actress-abduction-case-dileep-to-become-prime-accused/articleshow/61155047.cms |title=Actress abduction case: Dileep to become prime accused |website=The Times of India |access-date=16 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manoramaonline.com/news/latest-news/2017/07/01/actress-attack-case-police-raid-in-kavya-madhavan-s-online-textile-shop-office.html |title=Attack on Actress: search on Kavya Madhavan's textile showroom |work=Malayala Manorama |date=1 July 2017 |accessdate=1 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kochi/sit-questions-kavya-madhavan/articleshow/59762348.cms |title=Actor rape case: SIT questions Kavya Madhavan |work=The Times of India |date=26 July 2017 |accessdate=26 July 2017}}</ref><ref>[https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/regional-cinema/story/dileep-reinstated-in-amma-mohanlal-parvathy-bhavana-revathy-padmapriya-1272307-2018-06-28 Mollywood has set a horrible example by supporting Dileep \u2013 Movies News]. ''India Today''.in (28 June 2018). Retrieved 21 September 2018.</ref> On 10 July 2017, Dileep was arrested by [[Kerala Police]] for alleged conspiracy, and was remanded by the court.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/dileep-arrested-live-updates-actress-abduction-case-4744501/ |title=Kerala actor Dileep arrested on conspiracy charge in actress attack |date=11 July 2017 |work=The Indian Express}}</ref> On 3 October 2017, he was released on conditional bail by the [[Kerala High Court]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/actor-dileep-granted-bail-in-sexual-assault-case/article19790330.ece |title=Dileep granted bail in woman actor sexual assault case |first=K. c |last=Gopakumar |date=3 October 2017 |work=The Hindu}}</ref> In June 2018, he filed a petition in the Kerala High Court charging the Kerala Police of deliberately framing him. He requested the case be handed over to the [[Central Bureau of Investigation]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.india.com/showbiz/malayalam-actress-molestation-case-trial-begins-against-dileep-and-others-2943933/ |title=Dileep Appears in Court As Trial Begins in the Malayalam Actress Molestation Case |last=India |first=Press Trust of |date=14 March 2018 |work=India.com |access-date=24 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tactics-delay-trial-dileep-seeks-cbi-probe-malayalam-actor-abduction-case-82974 |title=Tactics to delay trial? Dileep seeks CBI probe in Malayalam actor abduction case |date=13 June 2018 |work=The News Minute |access-date=24 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his arrest, Dileep's membership was revoked by various film organisations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kochi/actor-dileep-expelled-from-amma-after-his-arrest/articleshow/59546651.cms |title=Actor Dileep expelled from AMMA after his arrest |work=The Times of India |date=11 July 2017 |accessdate=11 July 2017}}</ref> Several political parties protested against Dileep and his business firms were vandalised, including Dhe Puttu restaurant and the [[Multiplex (movie theater)|multiplex theatre]] D Cinemaas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/110717/mob-turns-violent-dileeps-business-firms-attacked.html |title=Mob turns violent, Dileep's business firms attacked |work=Deccan Chronicle |date=21 July 2017 |accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref> Dileep in the major prosecution process has filed an additional plea for accessing video footage of the incident. The plea was denied both the Angamaly Magistrate Court and Kerala High Court denied the plea. Mukul Rohatgi, a former [[Attorney General of India]] represented him in the case. In April 2019, the [[Government of Kerala]] froze charges against him until the court has given an independent verdict on the case.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/2017/jul/10/here-is-a-timeline-of-events-in-the-malayalam-actress-abduction-case-1626830.html |title=Here is a timeline of events in the Kerala actress abduction case |work=The New Indian Express |accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/news/kerala/2019/04/09/malayalam-superstar-dileep-actress-abduction-case.html |title=Malayalam superstar Dileep gets relief in abduction case &#124; English Manorama |publisher=English.manoramaonline.com |date=9 April 2019 |accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref> Mukul Rhotagi was able to get him a stay on the trial from Supreme Court thus making the case inactive until Dileep gets access to the video.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/india/malayalam-superstar-dileep-gets-relief-in-actress-kidnap-and-assault-case-1.1556902506786 |title=Malayalam superstar Dileep gets relief in actress kidnap and assault case |work=Gulf News |accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Main|Dileep filmography}}\n\n===Playback singing===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Song !! Film !! Year !! Lyrics !! Composer\n|-\n|\"Theme Music\"||''[[Chandranudikkunna Dikhil]]''|| 1999 || S. Ramesan Nair ||[[Vidyasagar (composer)|Vidhyasagar]]\n|- \n|\"Onnaam Malakeri\"|| ''[[Kalyanaraman (2002 film)|Kalyanaraman]]''|| 2002 || [[Kaithapram Damodaran]] || [[Berny-Ignatius]]\n|-\n|\"Saare Saare\" || ''[[Thilakkam]]'' || 2003 || Kaithapra