 Comedy Series|Comedy Series]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Jocelyn Bioh]], Flora Birnbaum, Cirocco Dunlap, Leslye Headland, Natasha Lyonne, Amy Poehler, [[Tami Sagher]] & Allison Silverman\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/writers-guild-awards-2020-tv-nominations-1203426148/ |title=Writers Guild Unveils 2020 TV Award Nominees |first=Dave |last=McNary |date=December 5, 2019 |accessdate=December 5, 2019 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" | [[Writers Guild of America Award for Television: New Series|New Series]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[Nebula Award]]\n|[[Ray Bradbury Award|The Ray Bradbury Nebula Award for Outstanding Dramatic Presentation]]\n|Allison Silverman and Leslye Headland <small>(for \"The Way Out\")</small> \n|{{pending}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nebulas.sfwa.org/award-year/2019/ |title=2019 - The Nebula Awards\u00ae |date=2019 |website=The Nebula Awards |publisher=Science Fiction & Fantasy Writers of America |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tor.com/2020/02/20/announcing-the-2019-nebula-awards-finalists/ |title=Announcing the 2019 Nebula Awards Finalists |date=February 20, 2020 |website=Tor.com |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[Hugo Award]]\n|[[Hugo Award for Best Dramatic Presentation|Best Dramatic Presentation, Long Form]]\n|Natasha Lyonne, Leslye Headland, Amy Poehler, Jamie Babbit (for Season One)\n|{{pending}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite web |title=2020 Hugo Awards |url=http://www.thehugoawards.org/hugo-history/2020-hugo-awards/ |publisher=World Science Fiction Society |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Netflix title|id=80211627}}\n* {{IMDb title|7520794}}\n\n{{Amy Poehler}}\n{{TCA Award for Outstanding New Program}}\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Russian Doll (TV series)}}\n[[Category:2010s American comedy-drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American mystery television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American time travel television series]]\n[[Category:2019 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:American science fiction web series]]\n[[Category:Comedy-drama web series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Fiction about memory erasure and alteration]]\n[[Category:Television series about Jews and Judaism]]\n[[Category:Mystery web series]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series about parallel universes]]\n[[Category:Television series by 3 Arts Entertainment]]\n[[Category:Television series by Paper Kite Productions]]\n[[Category:Television series by Universal Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows about death]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Time loop television series]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{short description|American comedy television series}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = Russian Doll\n| image              = RussianDoll.svg\n| genre              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Comedy-drama]]\n* [[Mystery fiction|Mystery]]\n}}\n| creator            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Natasha Lyonne]]\n* [[Leslye Headland]]\n* [[Amy Poehler]]\n}}\n| director           = {{Plainlist|\n* Leslye Headland\n* [[Jamie Babbit]]\n* Natasha Lyonne\n}}\n| starring           = {{Plainlist|\n* Natasha Lyonne\n* [[Greta Lee]]\n* [[Yul Vazquez]]\n* [[Charlie Barnett (actor)|Charlie Barnett]]\n* [[Elizabeth Ashley]]\n}}\n| composer           = [[Joe Wong (musician)|Joe Wong]]\n| country            = United States\n| language           = English\n| num_seasons        = 1\n| num_episodes       = 8\n| list_episodes      = #Episodes\n| executive_producer = {{Plainlist|\n* Natasha Lyonne\n* Leslye Headland\n* Amy Poehler\n* [[Dave Becky]]\n* Tony Hernandez\n* Lilly Burns\n* [[Allison Silverman]]\n}}\n| producer           = {{Plainlist|\n* Kate Arend\n* John Skidmore\n* Ryan McCormick\n}}\n| cinematography     = Chris Teague\n| editor             = {{Plainlist|\n* Todd Downing\n* Laura Weinberg\n}}\n| runtime            = 24\u201330 minutes\n| company            = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Universal Television]]\n* {{nowrap|[[Paper Kite Productions]]}}\n* [[Jax Media]]\n* [[3 Arts Entertainment]]\n* Avenue A\n* Shoot to Midnight\n}}\n| distributor        = [[NBCUniversal Television Distribution]]\n| network            = [[Netflix]]\n| first_aired        = {{Start date|2019|2|1}}\n| last_aired         = {{End date|present}}\n| website            = https://www.netflix.com/title/80211627\n| website_title      = Official website\n}}\n'''''Russian Doll''''' is an American [[comedy-drama]] [[web television]] series, created by [[Natasha Lyonne]], [[Leslye Headland]], and [[Amy Poehler]], that premiered on February 1, 2019, on [[Netflix]]. The series follows Nadia Vulvokov (Lyonne), a game developer who repeatedly dies and relives the same night in an ongoing [[time loop]] and tries to solve it, leading to her finding Alan Zaveri in the same situation (portrayed by [[Charlie Barnett (actor)| Charlie Barnett]]). It also stars [[Greta Lee]], [[Yul Vazquez]], and [[Elizabeth Ashley]].\n\nIts first season received four [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]] and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series]] for Lyonne. On June 11, 2019, Netflix renewed the series for a second season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/russian-doll-renewed-season-2-netflix-1203240080/|title='Russian Doll\u2019 Renewed for Season 2 at Netflix|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Joe|last=Otterson|date=June 11, 2019|accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref> \n\n==Premise==\n''Russian Doll'' follows a woman named Nadia on her journey as the guest of honor at a seemingly inescapable party one night in New York City. She dies repeatedly, always restarting at the same moment at the party, as she tries to figure out what is happening to her.<ref name=\"Trailer\">{{cite web |last=Ramos |first=Dino-Ray |title=\u2018Russian Doll\u2019 Trailer: Natasha Lyonne Relives Death On An Endless Loop In Netflix Comedy |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/russian-doll-trailer-netflix-natasha-lyonne-amy-poehler-leslye-headland-1202531787/ |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=January 9, 2019 |date=January 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Cast and characters==\n===Main===\n* [[Natasha Lyonne]] as Nadia Vulvokov, a software engineer who finds herself reliving her 36th birthday party in an ongoing time loop wherein she repeatedly dies and the process begins again.\n** Brooke Timber portrays Nadia as a child.\n* [[Greta Lee]] as Maxine, Nadia's friend, who throws her 36th birthday party.\n* [[Yul Vazquez]] as John Reyes, a real estate agent and Nadia's ex-boyfriend who is currently in the process of divorcing his wife.\n* [[Charlie Barnett (actor)|Charlie Barnett]] as Alan Zaveri, a man who is also stuck in a time loop like Nadia.\n* [[Elizabeth Ashley]] as Ruth Brenner, a therapist and close family friend of Nadia and her mother. \n:*[[Kate Jennings Grant]] portrays a young Ruth.\n\n===Recurring===\n* [[Dascha Polanco]] as Beatrice, Alan's girlfriend to whom he is going to propose\n* [[Jeremy Bobb]] as Mike Kershaw, a college literature professor with whom Beatrice is having an affair\n* [[Brendan Sexton III]] as Horse, a homeless man whom Nadia helps out\n* Rebecca Henderson as Lizzy, an artist and friend of Nadia and Maxine\n* [[Ritesh Rajan]] as Ferran, a friend of Alan's who works at the deli\n* Ken Beck as a [[paramedic]]\n* Max Knoblauch as a paramedic\n* Yoni Lotan as Ryan, a paramedic\n* [[Burt Young]] as Joe, a tenant in Alan's apartment building\n\n===Guest===\n{{div col}}\n* [[Waris Ahluwalia]] as Wardog, Maxine's drug dealer\n* [[David Cale]] as Dr. Daniel, a man who concocts the drugs that Wardog sells\n* [[Devin Ratray]] as a deli customer whom Nadia interrupts as he is purchasing a lottery ticket\n* [[Stephen Adly Guirgis]] as Peter, a client of Ruth's undergoing marital problems\n* [[Tami Sagher]] as Shifra, a secretary for the rabbi at the Tifereth Israel Synagogue\n* [[Jonathan Hadary]] as the rabbi at the Tifereth Israel Synagogue whom Nadia seeks out to ask questions about the building where her party was thrown\n* [[Lillias White]] as Dr. Zaveri, Alan's mother\n* [[Crystal Monee Hall]] as Jordanna, Lizzy's girlfriend\n* [[JD Samson]] as a [[Postmates]] delivery person\n* [[Michelle Buteau]] as a woman who pepper sprays Alan when she thinks he is stalking her.\n* [[Jocelyn Bioh]] as Claire\n* [[Chlo\u00eb Sevigny]] as Lenora Vulvokov, Nadia's mother with whom she had a difficult childhood\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#B30018 |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = Nothing in This World Is Easy\n |DirectedBy      = [[Leslye Headland]]\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=[[Natasha Lyonne]] & Leslye Headland & [[Amy Poehler]]|t=Leslye Headland}} \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|2|1}}\n |ShortSummary    = After dying abruptly on the night of her 36th birthday, Nadia finds herself reliving the events of the night in a continuous [[time loop]]. Every time Nadia dies, she returns to the bathroom of her friend Maxine's loft, where Nadia's birthday party is being thrown.\n |LineColor       = #B30018\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = The Great Escape\n |DirectedBy      = Leslye Headland\n |WrittenBy       = Natasha Lyonne & Amy Poehler\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|2|1}}\n |ShortSummary    = An increasingly frantic Nadia is convinced that she is hallucinating due to smoking one of Maxine's Israeli [[Joint (cannabis)|joints]] at her birthday party. She tracks down Maxine's drug dealer Wardog in order to find out what the joint was laced with.\n |LineColor       = B30018\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title           = A Warm Body\n |DirectedBy      = Leslye Headland\n |WrittenBy       = [[Allison Silverman]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|2|1}}\n |ShortSummary    = Nadia asks for John's help as her quest for answers leads her to a local [[synagogue]]. While searching for her cat Oatmeal, Nadia befriends a homeless man named Horse, and later encounters a mysterious man in a falling elevator.\n |LineColor       = B30018\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |Title           = Alan's Routine\n |DirectedBy      = [[Jamie Babbit]]\n |WrittenBy       = Cirocco Dunlap & Leslye Headland\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|2|1}}\n |ShortSummary    = The day before crossing paths with Nadia in the elevator, Alan plans to propose to his girlfriend Beatrice, only for her to break up with him. To make matters worse, Beatrice admits to cheating on Alan with her professor, Mike. Nadia tracks down Alan, since he is also experiencing time loops, but he accuses her of interfering with his routine.\n |LineColor       = B30018\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 5\n |Title           = Superiority Complex\n |DirectedBy      = Jamie Babbit\n |WrittenBy       = Jocelyn Bioh\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|2|1}}\n |ShortSummary    = Alan shows up at Nadia's birthday party and the two work together to figure out what is happening to them. Despite initially rebuffing Alan's theory that they are being punished for being bad people, Nadia sets out to make amends with John. Meanwhile, Alan confronts Mike about his affair with Beatrice.\n |LineColor       = B30018\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |Title           = Reflection\n |DirectedBy      = Jamie Babbit\n |WrittenBy       = Flora Birnbaum\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|2|1}}\n |ShortSummary    = In an effort to figure out how their lives are connected, Nadia helps Alan remember his first death as they retrace his steps. Alan eventually recalls he died as a result of suicide by throwing himself off the top of a building.\n |LineColor       = B30018\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 7\n |Title           = The Way Out\n |DirectedBy      = Leslye Headland\n |WrittenBy       = {{StoryTeleplay|s=Allison Silverman|t=Allison Silverman & Leslye Headland}}\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|2|1}}\n |ShortSummary    = With the steady disappearance of their loved ones, Nadia and Alan come up with a theory that the loops started because they neglected to help each other on the first night they died. Meanwhile, Nadia is haunted by memories of her troubled childhood.\n |LineColor       = B30018\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |Title           = Ariadne\n |DirectedBy      = Natasha Lyonne\n |WrittenBy       = Natasha Lyonne \n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|2|1}}\n |ShortSummary    = Nadia and Alan find themselves trapped in two separate timelines, where they run into alternate versions of each other who are in the first loop and unaware of the future loops.\n |LineColor       = B30018\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\nThe series was created by [[Natasha Lyonne]], [[Amy Poehler]], and [[Leslye Headland]], all of whom also serve as executive producers. Headland wrote the first episode, and she and Lyonne also serve as writers for the series. Production companies involved with the series consist of [[Universal Television]], [[Paper Kite Productions]], [[Jax Media]], and [[3 Arts Entertainment]].<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\">{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |title=Netflix Greenlights Comedy From Natasha Lyonne, Leslye Headland & Amy Poehler |url=http://deadline.com/2017/09/netflix-comedy-natasha-lyonne-leslye-headland-amy-poehler-1202173835/ |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=May 4, 2018 |date=September 20, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"HR1\">{{cite web |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |title=Natasha Lyonne to Star in Netflix Comedy From Amy Poehler, Leslye Headland |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/natasha-lyonne-star-netflix-comedy-amy-poehler-leslye-headland-1041520 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=May 4, 2018 |date=September 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=MacDonald |first=Lindsay |title=Amy Poehler Heads to Netflix With a Natasha Lyonne Comedy |url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/netflix-snags-amy-poehler-comedy-series-starring-natasha-lyonne/|website=[[TV Guide]] |accessdate=May 4, 2018 |date=September 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAlongside the initial series order announcement, it was confirmed that Lyonne would star in the series.<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\"/> Alongside the premiere announcement, it was confirmed that [[Greta Lee]], [[Yul Vazquez]], [[Elizabeth Ashley]], and [[Charlie Barnett (actor)|Charlie Barnett]] had joined the main cast and that [[Chlo\u00eb Sevigny]], [[Dascha Polanco]], [[Brendan Sexton III]], Rebecca Henderson, [[Jeremy Bobb]], [[Ritesh Rajan]], and [[Jocelyn Bioh]] would make guest appearances.\n\nPrincipal photography for season one began on February 22, 2018, in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|title=Thursday, Feb. 22 Filming Locations for Unbreakable Kimmy Schmidt, The OA, Younger, & more! - On Location Vacations|url=https://www.onlocationvacations.com/2018/02/21/thursday-feb-22-filming-locations-unbreakable-kimmy-schmidt-oa-younger/|website=On Location Vacations|accessdate=May 4, 2018|date=February 21, 2018}}</ref> In March 2020, filming for season two was delayed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/production-of-russian-doll-rutherford-falls-little-america-put-on-hold-by-uni-tv-amid-coronavirus-crisis-1202880611/ |title=Production Of 'Russian Doll', 'Rutherford Falls' & 'Little America' Put On Hold By Uni TV Amid Coronavirus Crisis |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\nThe song \"[[Gotta Get Up]]\" by American singer-songwriter [[Harry Nilsson]] was used as the \"reset\" song each time the character Nadia dies and is resurrected. Lyonne explained to ''[[The New York Times]]'' that in choosing the song she was struck by the \"buoyant doomsday quality\" of Nilsson's life. Other contenders for the reset song included \"[[Not Tonight]]\" by [[Lil' Kim]], \"Crazy Feeling\" by [[Lou Reed]] and \"[[No Fun (song)|No Fun]]\" by [[The Stooges]]. Though Netflix finally obtained the usage rights to Nilsson's song, the cost of using it so many times took up a significant portion of the music budget. His estate also limited how many times the song could be used. According to music supervisor Brienne Rose, the production was able to \"find a balance between the maximum number of uses and what the budget would allow.\" The \"reset\" song utilized for the character Alan was [[Beethoven]]'s \"[[Piano Concerto No. 4 (Beethoven)|Piano Concerto No. 4 In G Major]]\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Harris |first=Aisha |title=This Is That Song From \u2018Russian Doll\u2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/01/arts/television/russian-doll-netflix-harry-nilsson-gotta-get-up.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=February 9, 2019 |date=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nOn January 9, 2019, Netflix released the first trailer for the series.<ref name=\"Trailer\"/> On January 23, 2019, the series held its official premiere at the Metrograph theater in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. Those in attendance included series writer Jocelyn Bioh, [[Taylor Schilling]], [[Natasha Lyonne]], [[Fred Armisen]], [[Amy Poehler]], [[Chlo\u00eb Sevigny]], [[Greta Lee]], [[Dascha Polanco]], [[Rosie O'Donnell]], [[Danielle Brooks]], [[Laura Prepon]], and [[David Harbour]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Kirsch |first=Daniela |title=Natasha Lyonne, David Harbour At Netflix 'Russian Doll' Premiere |url=https://patch.com/new-york/new-york-city/natasha-lyonne-david-harbour-netflix-russian-doll-premiere |website=[[Patch Media]] |accessdate=February 1, 2019 |date=January 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Bobila |first=Maria |title=Greta Lee Wore a Balenciaga Throwback From the Nicolas Ghesqui\u00e8re Days |url=https://fashionista.com/2019/01/greta-lee-balenciaga-spring-2008-russian-doll-premiere |website=[[Fashionista (website)|Fashionista]] |accessdate=February 1, 2019 |date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe series has received critical acclaim. On the review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the series holds a 96% approval rating with an average rating of 8.53 out of 10 based on 85 reviews. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Russian Doll'' may be stuck in a time loop, but this endlessly inventive series never repeats itself as it teeters on a seesaw of shifting tones \u2013 from fatally funny to mournfully sad \u2013 that is balanced with exhilarating moxie by an astonishing Natasha Lyonne.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Russian Doll: Season 1 |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/russian_doll/s01 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media|Fandango]] |accessdate=May 28, 2019}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted average, assigned the series a score of 89 out of 100 based on 24 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Russian Doll: Season 1 |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/russian-doll/season-1 |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlicia Lutes of [[IGN]] gave the first season a 10/10. Praising the series, she adds that it is \"an inventive, unpredictable ride that will easily stand as one of the best shows of the year.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://au.ign.com/articles/2019/02/14/netflixs-russian-doll-review-season-1|title=Netflix's Russian Doll: Season 1 Review|last=Lutes|first=Alicia|publisher=IGN|date=February 14, 2019|accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref> In a positive review, ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s [[Alan Sepinwall]] awarded the series {{frac|4|1|2}} stars out of 5 and praised it saying, \"That blend of tones, and the controlled mania of Lyonne's brilliant performance, makes ''Russian Doll'' feel like something wholly new, even as it cops to its many influences.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |title=\u2018Russian Doll\u2019 Review: Natasha Lyonne Is a Revelation |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/tv/tv-reviews/russian-doll-review-natasha-lyonne-netflix-784649/ |website=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=February 2, 2019 |date=January 29, 2019}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}} [[James Poniewozik]] was similarly approving saying, \"''Russian Doll'' is lean and snappily paced; it even managed the rare feat, in the era of streaming-TV bloat, of making me wish for a bit more.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Poniewozik |first=James |title=\u2018Russian Doll\u2019: Repetitive Death Syndrome |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/31/arts/television/russian-doll-netflix-review.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=February 2, 2019 |date=January 31, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Collider (website)|Collider]]''{{'}}s Haleigh Foutch was equally enthusiastic giving the series a rating of 5 out of 5 stars and applauding it saying, \"It's pure binge-watching magic; a show that's not only expertly designed to compel viewers to the next episode but invests just as much in the integrity of story and character.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Foutch |first=Haleigh |title='Russian Doll' Review: Netflix's Comedy Is a Wickedly Clever Fable of Morality & Mortality |url=http://collider.com/russian-doll-netflix-review |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |accessdate=February 1, 2019 |date=February 1, 2019}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s Judy Berman described the series as \"cerebral yet propulsive\" and praised its many layers calling it, \"2019's best new show to date.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Berman |first1=Judy |title=Netflix's Russian Doll Is 2019's Best Show So Far |url=http://time.com/5509932/russian-doll-netflix-review/ |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=February 9, 2019 |date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:98%\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3%;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:22%;\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:33%;\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:35%;\"| Nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:6%;\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:1%;\"| {{Abbr|Ref.|References}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"22\"| 2019\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"4\"| [[35th TCA Awards|Television Critics Association Awards]]\n| colspan=\"2\"|[[TCA Award for Program of the Year|Program of the Year]]\n| {{nom}}\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"4\"|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/pose-russian-doll-hbo-lead-2019-tv-critic-awards-nominations-1219571 |title='Pose,' 'Russian Doll,' HBO Lead 2019 TV Critic Awards Nominations |website=The Hollywood Reporter |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |date=June 19, 2019 |accessdate=June 22, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"|[[TCA Award for Outstanding Achievement in Comedy|Outstanding Achievement in Comedy]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\"|[[TCA Award for Outstanding New Program|Outstanding New Program]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[TCA Award for Individual Achievement in Comedy|Individual Achievement in Comedy]]\n| [[Natasha Lyonne]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"4\"| [[71st Primetime Emmy Awards|Primetime Emmy Awards]]\n| colspan=\"2\"|[[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]]\n| {{nominated}}\n| align=\"center\" rowspan=\"13\"|<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2019/09/22/emmys-2019-awards-winners-list/ |title=Emmys 2019: Game of Throne